The Manufacturing edition of Acumatica ERP deliver powerful and comprehensive functionality for make-to-stock, make-to-order, engineer-to-order, project-centric, job shop, batch, and repetitive manufacturing companies. It is an easy-to-use and powerful solution designed to be used by a wide range of organizations with simple to advanced business flow and reporting needs.{br}

In this topic, you will find information about parts of Manufacturing edition.
==Bills of Material==
The Bills of Material (BOM)/Routing part creates production specifications and is the framework for the planning functionality in all Manufacturing edition parts. Maintenance of the BOM/Routing information is performed through a single form. You directly connect materials, work instructions, tools, attributes, and overhead costs to an operation. It provides for revision tracking, phantom assemblies, backflushing of both labor and materials, material effectivity dates, by-products, and alternate bills of materials.{br}

For more information, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_BOM_Features|Bills of Material: General Information].
==Production Management==
The Production Management part provides you with easy entry of production orders, quick release of planned production orders, availability of using alternate BOMs and routing by using revisions, an event history, and easy release of materials. {br}

For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PM_Features|Production Management: General Information]
==Material Requirements Planning (MRP)==
The Material Requirements Planning (MRP) part provides you with the ability to schedule full regeneration for planning what materials will be need to be purchased or produced, as well as plan production and purchase orders. {br}

For more information, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_MRP_Features|Material Requirements Planning: General Information].
==Estimating==
The optional Estimating part is integrated with manufacturing, customer management, and sales orders. It provides users with the ability to create quick and detailed manufacturing estimates for improved estimate accuracy and turnaround times. Users can accurately calculate costs and prices for new or existing parts using material costs, work center rates, overheads, and other data.{br}

For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_EST_Features|Estimating: General Information].
==Product Configurator==
The optional Product Configurator part is integrated with manufacturing, customer management, and sales orders. It is a rule-based system designed to provide users the ability to configure, order, and build to order inventory items.{br}

For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PC_Features|Product Configurator: General Information].
==Advanced Planning and Scheduling==
The optional Advanced Planning and Scheduling (APS) part provides the ability to finitely schedule production orders based on work center capacity. This functionality extends the production management functionality.{br}

For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_APS_Features|Advanced Planning and Scheduling: General Information].
==Engineering Change Control==
The optional Engineering Change Control (ECC) part provides a workflow process to approve and update bills of material. This feature extends the bills of material functionality.{br}

For more information, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_ECC_Features|Engineering Change Control: General Information].

The production management functionality supports the backflushing of both materials and labor. The defaults are defined in the bill of material using [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]) which defaults for each operation from the work center settings when creating the bill. Flexibility is provided by configuring backflushing for only specific materials and/or operations. The configuration of backflushing starts with the work center. *You can check the Backflush Materials and/or Backflush Labor for a work center by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form to provide default values for operations added to a bill of material. *When you add an operation to the bill of material you can select or clear the backflush option for labor and/or material. *When you add the materials for an operation you can select or clear the backflush option for any material.
When you report production for an operation by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]) form and a quantity is entered, the following occurs: *Any materials where the backlashed flag is checked will be issued to the production order from the warehouse/location specified in the material line or if empty from the default issue from warehouse/location. The [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PM_BinLocations|How Warehouse Locations Are Selected] topic explains how locations are determined. *If there are prior operations with backflush checked for materials, the quantity to issue is calculated as the difference between the actual quantity reported at that operation and this operation multiplied by the quantity per. This can result is a negative issue if the prior operation had material issued. *If there are prior operations with the backflush labor checked the labor amount will be adjusted if necessary to agree with the quantity reported at the current operation vs. the quantity previously reported.
The purpose of the recalculations is to reconcile any quantity differences between the current operation and any prior operations and adjust the costs charged to the production order accordingly.{br}
If you decide to backflush materials, please note the following: *The process creates a Materials batch on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form, which is automatically released. *It cannot issue more materials than what is on hand in a location unless negative inventories are allowed. *The locations are determined according the rules specified in [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PM_BinLocations|How Warehouse Locations Are Selected].
==What is Backflushing?== Backflushing is a method for issuing materials and/or labor to production orders at the point that production of a specific operation is reported. This is commonly referred to as ''&ldquo;postproduction issuing&ldquo;'', vs. ''&ldquo;preproduction issuing&ldquo;'' where materials are pulled from stores and issued to production orders prior to the start of an operation and labor is directly reported for each operation.{br}
Material and labor costs are flushed backwards through operations to assign costs to products based on the quantity of product produced at the operations. The result is that detailed tracking of costs is eliminated. This can represent a time savings over the traditional method of a) issuing component parts one at a time, b) reporting operation labor or quantities, and c) returning any unused components, one at a time, back into inventory.{br}
Additionally, backflushing can ensure that the full cost of production is recognized when the final operation is reported and the finished product is received into inventory. The backflushing process will adjust the materials consumed and/or labor reported for any operations where the full amount has not been posted. The receipt cost of the product can be more representative and/or variances are minimized. ==When is Backflushing Appropriate?== #In operations where scrap is common in the finished item and you continue to produce until you have a good quantity equal to the ordered quantity. You would report both the good quantity and scrap quantity to ensure the proper quantities of materials and labor. #Only certain milestone operations are reported and prior operations are backflushed to account for the labor cost. Or inspection operations are performed by sampling. #Operations are performed for multiple production orders at the simultaneously or in a continuous run such as cleaning, painting, plating, etc. where it would be difficult to post labor to individual orders. Similarly, there may be production areas or lines where multiple operators work on whatever item appears at their work station such as filling, testing, packing, or assembly and do not report their time against specific orders. #There are floor stock items, such as lubricants, labels, hardware, wiring, packing materials, etc., in the bill of material whose costs are not significant. An expense issue is performed periodically to reconcile the on hand balance to the physical inventory. #When you use point-of-use materials, backflushing simplifies the issuing process and makes it easier to perform counts on the point-of-use materials. If you were to preproduction issue these materials you would need to reconcile the inventory balances with any orders that had quantities staged to the production area but not yet consumed, however, if by backflushing you should have a system-to-actual-count match after each production posting. #In very long production runs (days or weeks) where preproduction posting takes the materials out of the on-hand inventory balance days or weeks before they are being used and puts the dollar value into a WIP account for the production order. You also may have situations where you do not have enough of the raw materials for the entire production run, however, more will be arriving during the run. #When you are using bulk materials such as bar stock, roll stock, sheet goods, and dry goods or liquids in bulk containers, where the exact quantity cannot be picked. For example, if you need 1000 linear feet of material that comes in bulk rolls of 300 linear feet, preproduction issuing of 1000 even though the material handler delivered 1200 causes a confusing inventory situation, and issuing the entire 1200 would require you to reverse issue 200 when you return the remainder.
==When is Backflushing Not Appropriate?== #The amount of labor applied to an operation can have variances from one production run to another. The labor amount may represent a significant cost of the product. #When employees are accountable for the product being produced and traceability is desired. #Lot and/or serialized materials must be verified and recorded as being issued. Although backflushing can automatically issue lot- or serial-tracked items it is generally not recommended. #Materials consumption is variable or there is significant waste of a particular material. #Material substitutions are common and allowed during the production process. #Labor transactions by employee need to be reconciled to time and attendance for payroll purposes or a shop data collection system is used. ((({S:Warn}When you have materials stored in multiple physical bin locations there is guarantee material was picked from the backflush location. )))

By-products are secondary products from the manufacturing process for the primary product.((({S:Hint}If you are going to use lot control for by-products and you are going to backflush them, you must set up the lot class for sequential issue. ))) If you do not wish to have a cost for the by-product credited to the primary product cost, then set the valuation method of the by-product to ''Standard Cost'' and set a standard cost of zero or make sure not to do any receipts for the by-product with a cost for average, FIFO, or specific cost.{br}{TOC} ==Setting up the Bill of Material for By-Products== Any material component with a negative quantity required is considered a by-product. The cost of a by-product is credited to the cost of the primary product if the by-product has a cost. For example: {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !'''Component''' ! '''Qty Required''' ! '''Unit Cost''' |- | CHEMCOMP1 | .05 Liters | 1.00 |- | CHEMCOMP2 | .06 Liters | 1.00 |- | CHENBYPROD1 | -.01 Liters | 1.00 |} The material cost per liter is $1.00: (.05 x $1.00) + (.06 x $1.00) + (-.01 x $1.00). ==By-Products and Production Orders== When a production order is created, any items with a negative quantity per unit required will have the by-product flag checked. Similarly, you must enter a negative quantity per unit required for a by-product you add to a production order manually. The cost of the by-product, if any, is calculated and deducted from the planned material and total cost of the production order when creating the production order. The by-product flag on the production details is used when creating a materials batch to indicate that this item will be received into inventory. An Inventory Receipt transaction is created to receive the by-product into inventory.{br}
The receipt cost of a by-product is determined using the Item Warehouse cost; this is the same method used to determine the cost of all materials. The by-product is not credited with any of the production costs. This is generally accepted method for handling by-products.{br}
''When compared to the main products, because they are deemed to have no influence on reported financial results, by-products do not receive allocations of joint costs. By-products also by convention are not inventoried, but the NRV from by-products is typically recognized as other income or as a reduction of joint production processing costs when the by-product is produced. A by-product can be useful and marketable or it can be considered waste.''((({S:Hint}This information has been copied from the following sources:[anchor|#_16667c08-e181-460f-aef9-52736bd3790a] #Wouters, Mark; Selto, Frank H.; Hilton, Ronald W.; Maher, Michael W. (2012): ''Cost Management: Strategies for Business Decisions'', International Edition, McGraw-Hill, p. 535. #World Trade Organization (2004): United States - Final dumping determination on softwood lumber from Canada, WT/DS264/AB/R, 11 August 2004. )))

These are the accounts, and if configured, subaccounts used on the manufacturing forms specified directly or indirectly. ==General Ledger Accounts Used in Manufacturing== The work in process (WIP) account and subaccount and the WIP Variance account and subaccount are required in order to create production orders and are specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form or if not used, then on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form. The Work in Progress account should be of the ''Asset'' type and the WIP Variance should be of the ''Expense'' type. This account should not be used as an inventory or expense account in order to be able to balance the account in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\AM_65_40_00|Work in Process] ([~/?ScreenId=AM654000|AM654000]) report.{br}
Transactions for production orders debit the work in process account and credit the offset account for each cost element. A reversing transaction does the opposite. Upon closing a production order the WIP Variance account is posted and the WIP Balance is zeroed and the appropriate debit and credit generated.((({S:Warn}At this time the '''Control Account''' validation feature is not supported when specifying the accounts on manufacturing forms. ))) If production scrap will be reported and expensed, then you need to specify the appropriate reason codes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) form with their GL accounts for the scrap expense. For more details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_Scrap|Handling Production Scrap and Waste].{br}
Labor codes must also be set up by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_65_00|Labor Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=AM206500|AM206500]) form. Labor codes are required when setting up work cnters on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form. If indirect time will be reported, then an indirect labor account is also required or you may use the same account as for direct labor.{br}
If overhead, tooling, r machine costs are to be charged to production orders then each requires an offset account to be defined on the following forms:[anchor|#_35e30657-86b6-47e0-9a62-0a328f59c75a] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_25_00|Overhead] ([~/?ScreenId=AM202500|AM202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_55_00|Tools] ([~/?ScreenId=AM205500|AM205500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_45_00|Machines] ([~/?ScreenId=AM204500|AM204500]) ((({S:Hint}You need to consider the impact of posting to the non-inventory accounts (labor, overhead, machines, and tooling) in production management. Typically, the actual manufacturing expenses such payroll and benefits, utilities, depreciation, purchased tooling, repairs and maintenance, etc. are posted to the General Ledger into cost of sales accounts. The labor, overhead, tools, and/or machine accounts could be set up as balance sheet accrual accounts or income statement contra expense accounts that would be debited to zero when posting the actual costs. ))) In the following table, you can view the list of GL accounts used in manufacturing.[anchor|#_7efc600a-3dfd-437d-9542-20315543acb4] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="33%" ! Category !width="33%" ! Debit Account !width="33%" ! Credit Account |- | colspan="3" | '''Bill of Material''' |- | Direct Labor | (WIP Account) | Labor Account |- | Indirect | Indirect Labor Expense | Labor Account |- | Overhead | (WIP Account) | Overhead Account |- | Tools | (WIP Account) | Tooling Account |- | Machine | (WIP Account) | Machine Account |- | colspan="3" | '''Production Management ''' |- | Work in Process | WIP Account | (Inventory) or expense |- | WIP Variance | WIP Variance | WIP Account |}((({S:Warn}The Inventory account and subaccount is copied from the stock item&rsquo;s Inventory account when material is issued or received; if the item issued is non-stock, then the Expense Accrual account is used. Labor expense is copied from the account and subaccount specified for the labor code; other costs that are automatically calculated such as overhead, tooling, or machine costs, use the expense account specified. If labor is backflushed, then the labor expense account is copied from the labor code associated with the first shift code of the work center specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form. )))

''Waste'' is a loss of materials inputted into the production process and is specified by the '''Scrap Factor''' assigned to the material in the bill of material. For example, during the cutting of a material 5% waste is expected. The quantity, and resultant total cost, of a material required is scaled up by the scrap factor. The wasted material does not have value although some costs may be recovered if the waste can be recycled such as metal filings, wood chips, and plastics.{br}

By-products are also production output and are typically treated as ''waste'' because production costs are not allocated to them. They can, however, have a standard cost which is used to credit the production order with their value when received into inventory.{br}

''Scrap'' is a loss from production output; that is the item being produced does not meet its specifications. In this case, the scrap can have a value representing the accrued production costs. The item may be reworked to meet specifications, sold as-is at a discounted price, used as input to another process, or discarded.{br}{TOC}
==Options for Scrap Accounting ==
There are the following methods available to account for the cost of production scrap (for details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_Scrap_Processing_Configuration|Scrap Processing Configuration]):
*'''No Action''': The cost of scrap remains in the production order and no scrap transaction is generated
*'''Write-off''': The cost is written off and charged to an expense account
*'''Quarantine''': The scrap is received into inventory to a quarantined location and dispositioned later
((({S:Hint}The '''Include Scrap in Completions''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form is still used to determine if an operation is closed automatically. The receipt cost calculation ignores the total scrap for all scrap that has been written off and will not include those quantities in the receipt cost calculation. If scrap is not written off, then the scrap quantity is included or excluded based on the setting.
)))
In the latter two methods, the cost of the scrap is the accrued production cost which debits the scrap expense account and credits the work in process account of the production order. If the quarantine option is used, the inventory on hand balance is adjusted at the quarantine warehouse and location; the ''Ext. Cost'' is the calculated scrap cost.{br}

Negative scrap, typically to correct a transaction, is permitted and the transactions have the opposite effect.{br}

The actual transactions are generated on the following forms:
*[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_80_00|WIP Adjustment] ([~/?ScreenId=AM308000|AM308000]): On this form, a GL transaction is generated to credit the production order WIP account and debit the Scrap Expense account specified by the reason code. The WIP adjustment is recorded on the '''Production Order Events''' tab.
*[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=IN303000|IN303000]): Additionally, if the scrap action is '''Quarantine''', an inventory adjustment is created and released. The GL transaction created by the adjustment debits the Inventory account and credits the Scrap Expense account.
*:((({S:Warn} If the stock item has a valuation method of standard cost, then an inventory account is posted at standard cost and the standard cost adjustment is generated for the difference; the credit for scrap expense is the actual cost.
)))
((({S:Warn}The costs calculated for negative scrap may differ from the original transaction if additional costs have been posted to the operations used to calculate the cost.
)))
==Impact on Inventory Valuation==
If you choose to use the scrap action of '''Quarantine''' the inventory adjustment will update the current cost. ((({S:Warn}For this reason we recommend that you either create a separate warehouse, or select the '''Cost Separately''' check box for the warehouse location, for the quarantined inventory to ensure the scrap cost does not affect the cost of accepted inventory when the item valuation method is ''FIFO'' or ''Average Cost''.
)))
If the item valuation method is ''Standard'', you select the '''Override Standard Cost''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. If the item valuation method is ''Specific'', then you can use the same warehouse however, the last cost and average cost values will still include the scrap cost adjustment.
==Scrap Cost Calculation==
The scrap cost calculations are dependent on the costing method specified for the production order.{br}

'''Actual Costing Method'''{br}

To calculate the actual cost of scrap, the cost of each production operation is calculated. The cost of the scrap includes the actual costs for the current operation for which scrap is reported plus the estimated costs of prior operations. The estimated costs for prior operations is the sum of actual plus planned costs to account for materials, labor, and other costs not reported; that is a material was not issued to a prior operation so its planned unit cost will be factored into the operation cost totals.{br}

The WIP balance for each operation is the total actual costs posted minus the ''MFG to Inventory'' (that is, the total costs of receipts to inventory) totals. The formula used for calculation of each operation is the following:{{{{AMProdOper.WIPBalance / (AMProdOper.QtyComplete + AMProdOper.QtyScrapped - 
AMProdItem.QtyComplete) * AMMTran.QtyScrapped
}}}}
{{AMProdOper.QtyComplete}} includes the adjusted amount for transaction move quantity or scrap.{br}

'''Estimated or Standard Costing Method'''{br}

The only difference between these costing methods and the ''Actual'' costing method is these methods will factor in the planned costs to the WIP Balance for missing costs; such as labor or materials overhead that have not been reported. For example, all of the materials needed to produce the item at an operation were not issued.
==Processing Scrap in Production Transactions==
You can enter the scrapped quantity to both the labor and move transactions.{br}

When the ''Qty Scrapped'' is not 0 and the scrap action is not ''No Action'', a WIP adjustment transaction is created for the scrap cost.[anchor|#_c8d1c084-f35a-4698-9ab6-7cb0884cdf22]
*The ''Orig Batch Nbr'' and ''Orig Doc Type'' link back to the source transaction.
*The reason code entered determines the Scrap Expense account and subaccount.
*The table with details include the production order values for the operation, scrap quantity, and any inventory adjustment created.
*The scrap warehouse and scrap location are defaulted from the production order.

A GL transaction is created when the WIP adjustment is released to post to the scrap expense production order WIP account.{br}

If the scrap action is ''Quarantine'' you must enter the move or labor transaction on a separate line and select the '''Is Scrap''' check box. This is required in order to specify the scrap warehouse, location, and if required, the lot/serial number.
==Reporting Options==
To create an inquiry or report for the scrap activity the {{AMTran}} Data Access Class will have the {{DocType}} set to ''W'' and the {{TranType}} set to either of the following:[anchor|#_5208e065-f4fb-4d18-85a3-c5c69f5d0fdd]
*''XSW'': Scrap Write-Off
*''XSQ'': Scrap Quarantine

In this topic, you will read about configuring scrap processing.{br}{TOC} ==Reason Codes== Reason codes created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) form specify the GL account and subaccount to be used for the scrap expense. A reason code is required when reporting scrap if the scrap action is ''Write-off'' or ''Quarantine''. The usage of the reason code must be ''Production Scrap''. The '''Combine Sub. From''' box determines masks for reason code, stock item, posting class, or warehouse. You can create multiple reason codes for scrap with the same or different GL accounts and subaccounts. ==Scrap Action== The scrap action determines how scrap is processed. The default actions are set on the following forms:[anchor|#_91ef5c51-c966-4de1-9151-5246a459ebcf] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]), which inherits the action from the work center *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]), which inherits the actions from the bill of material when the production order is created.
The labor and move transactions inherit the values from the production order operation and can be overriden.{br}
In the following table, you can see the list of scrap actions with descriptions.[anchor|#_dc29b5f8-ba25-419c-83e1-c4951a08b192] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Action !Value (for reports) !Description |- | ''No Action'' | 0 | Scrap can be reported but its cost remains on the production order. This is the prior method for handling scrap. |- | ''Write-Off'' | 1 | Scrap cost is charged to the scrap expense account. |- | ''Quarantine'' | 2 | Scrap cost is charged to the scrap expense account and an inventory adjustment is created for the scrap quantity and value. |} ==Scrap Warehouse and Scrap Location== For the ''Quarantine'' action, scrap is adjusted in a warehouse and location. They are copied from the values set on the '''General''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form. These boxes are only available if the ''Multiple Warehouses'' and ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' features are enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.{br}
These values can be set on the following forms:[anchor|#_ed0c5ad9-edca-4d10-9ba1-f781f47bc970] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]), the '''Manufacturing''' tab. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]), the '''Manufacturing''' tab. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]), the '''Manufacturing''' tab. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]), the '''General Settings''' tab.
==Scrap Source== The scrap source determines the default values for the '''Scrap Warehouse''' and '''Scrap Location''' boxes when a production order is created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form. You specify the default value of the scrap source on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form. The default values for the '''Scrap Warehouse''' and '''Scrap Location''' boxes of a production order are copied as follows:[anchor|#_cad06ad5-1573-44e6-b220-3591e00e0cbe] #If the scrap source is ''None'', no default values are used. #If the scrap source is ''Item'', the scrap warehouse and scrap location are copied from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. ##If the values on this form are empty, the system uses the values from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. ##If the values on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form are also empty, the system uses the values from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form. #If the scrap source is ''Warehouse'', the system uses the values from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form. If the values on this form are empty, the system uses the values from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form. #If the scrap source is ''Order Type'', the system uses the values from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form.
==Scrap Override== When you select the '''Scrap Override''' check box on the '''General''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form, you can override the scrap warehouse and scrap location defaults.

A new method to calculate requirements for inventory items has been added. This enhancement affects all forms and processes where material quantities are calculated; bills of material, production orders, MRP, estimates, and options for product configurations. ==Quantity Round Up== On the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, the '''Forecast Round Up''' check box has been replaced with the '''Quantity Round Up''' check box, which is cleared by default.{br}
The purpose is to round up any calculations of the quantity required to the next integer value. This is particularly useful for inventory items stocked in units without decimals such as ''Each'' or ''Unit''. The round up is applied to the unit of measure specified for the requirement; that is, if the base stocking unit is ounce and pound is specified as the unit of measure for a production order, then the requirement is rounded up the next pound. ==Batch Size== The batch size is also used in calculating the quantity required for inventory items. Previously, all material requirements were specified as per unit of the parent item. With the batch size supported, now the quantity required can be calculated as per lot size of the parent. As with quantity round up, batch size is used on all calculations of inventory quantities required.{br}
The ''lot size'' term refers to the quantity of the parent inventory item being produced. The parent lot size is set on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form and can be overridden on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. The lot size becomes the default for MRP planned orders and production orders and is used in the cost roll process of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_80_00|Cost Roll] ([~/?ScreenId=AM508000|AM508000]) form. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_30_00|Estimate] ([~/?ScreenId=AM303000|AM303000]) form, the '''Order Qty''' on the '''Totals''' tab is used as the lot size.{br}
The quantity to produce is the lot size for production orders and the materials required are calculated on that basis. Changing the quantity to produce recalculates the requirements.{br}
Batch size settings are the following:[anchor|#_d2252371-6c6a-4687-94aa-e349f9ebb114] *Batch Size of One (1): The quantity required of a component is per unit of the parent inventory item. This is the default value. *Batch Size of Zero (0): The quantity required is fixed regardless of the parent lot size. *Batch Size Greater than One (1): The quantity required is divided by the batch size.
==Added Calculation Columns== In the following table, you can view columns that have been added where appropriate to assist users in visualizing the effect of the batch size and quantity round up functionality. {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Element !Description |- | '''Total Qty (Operations)''' | The '''Quantity to Produce''' value in a production order for an operation less accumulated scrap (if the '''Include Scrap in Completions''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form). |- | '''Qty Remaining (Operations)''' | Calculated as '''Total Qty''' minus '''Qty Complete''' |- | '''Total Required''' | The quantity of a material required based on the '''Batch Size''' and '''Quantity Round Up''' values. |- | '''Qty Remaining (Materials)''' | Calculated as '''Total Required''' minus '''Qty Actual'''. |} ==Total Quantity Required Examples== The examples below show the effect of the batch size and quantity round up functionality. The same material requirement is used. {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Inventory ID !Qty Required !Batch Size !Total Qty Required !With Qty Round Up !Order Qty |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 1 | 7.000 | 7.000 | 10.000 |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 0 | 0.700 | 1.000 | 10.000 |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 2 | 3.500 | 4.000 | 10.000 |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 1 | 17.500 | 18.000 | 25.000 |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 0 | 0.700 | 1.000 | 25.000 |- | COMPSTD | 0.700 | 2 | 8.750 | 9.000 | 25.000 |} ==Forms Modified== In this section, you can find the list of boxes that have been added to forms. Some of the new boxes are hidden by default but can be added by using the column selector for each table. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]), the '''Material''' table **'''Batch Size''' (hidden) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]), the '''Manufacturing''' tab **'''Quantity Round Up''' (has been renamed from '''Forecast Round Up''') *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]), the '''Operations''' table **'''Total Qty''' (hidden) **'''Qty Remaining''' * [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]), the '''Materials''' table **'''Batch Size''' (hidden) **'''Total Required''' ** '''Qty Remaining''' ** '''Qty Round Up''' * [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_40_00|Estimate Operation] ([~/?ScreenId=AM304000|AM304000]), the '''Materials''' table **'''Batch Size''' (hidden) **'''Total Required''' ** '''Qty Round Up '''(hidden) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_35_00|Features] ([~/?ScreenId=AM203500|AM203500]), the '''Options''' table **'''Batch Size''' (hidden) **'''Qty Round Up '''(hidden) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_75_00|Configuration Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207500|AM207500]), the '''Options''' table **'''Batch Size''' (hidden) **'''Qty Round Up '''(hidden)

You can import master data related to manufacturing by using import scenarios on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_36|Import by Scenario] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206036|SM206036]) form. In this topic, you will find information that will help you to import data. Also, you will find the Excel spreadsheets that you can use during import.((({S:Hint}The format of all time values (Setup, Run, Machine, and Move) is specified in the '''Operation Time Format''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_10_00|BOM Preferences] form. Times are now entered or displayed as in days, hours, and minutes. Regardless of the format, you can enter the time as 0000 for HHMM or 000000 for DDHHMM. Time values are actually stored as minutes in the tables. For importing, enter the time as HHMM; e,g. 0010 for 10 minutes, 0130 for 1 hour 30 minutes, 011013 for 1 day, 10 hours, 13 minutes. ))){br}{TOC} ==General Information== Almost all of the master data is related to bills of material functionality consisting of the bills of material for each assembly and their supporting data such as work centers, tools, machines, and overhead. For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_Import_BOM|Importing Bills of Material Master Data].{br}
