Lead times are used to indicate when an action needs to take place. For example, the required date for a purchase order is offset by the lead time to determine when the action date when a purchase order should be placed.((({S:Hint}Vendor lead times in Acumatica ERP are in calendar days. The working days, used for manufactured items are configured by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_90_00|Work Calendar] ([~/?ScreenId=CS209000|CS209000]) form. ))) There can be multiple work calendars each with different time zones, working hours, and exceptions. An exception would be making a calendar holiday a non-working day or the reverse of making a weekend date a working day.{br}{TOC} ==Lead Time Components== Your lead time should account for the total time it takes when you recognize a demand to the when the item is available to be shipped. This would include the time necessary to review requirements, source and select how it will be acquired (for example, do you find potential suppliers and get quotes, or does engineering need to review it?), prepare a requisition if necessary, obtain approval, create the order, send it to supplier or plant, vendor/factory production time, transport time from supplier/plant to distribution point, receiving and inspection.{br}
The purpose of a lead time is to provide you with sufficient time to source purchased items or to start and complete production processes in order to satisfy customer demand. Padding lead times with excessive days may lead to placing or starting orders too far in advance and do not necessarily improve on-time delivery or completion performance. ==How Manufacturing Uses Calendars with Lead Times== There are multiple forms (listed below) where you select a working calendar to use. When computing dates, the appropriate calendar is used. *Bill of Material **[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]): The calendar is used to determine the working days available hours each day and is used when calculating operation planned start and completion dates for variable lead times. *Production Management **[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]): You can specify a global calendar to use to fixed manufacturing lead times and indicate if you will set manufacturing fixed lead times to be hours or days. **[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]): You can decide whether to use fixed manufacturing days for an individual production order *Material Requirements Planning **[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]): A calendar is specified to be used for purchase orders.
==Purchase Lead Times== Purchase lead time are always fixed and not variable by order quantity so you should set them based on a typical order size. The lead times for items having a replenishment source of Purchasing use the lead time from the default vendor location which can be adjusted for a specific item and warehouse. If an item does not have a default vendor the lead time from the Manufacturing tab is used. For example, the lead time for a vendor location is 10 calendar days but certain items may need additional 5 days or require 5 less days. The MRP Regeneration process uses the purchase lead time to calculate the action date; if the action date is not a working day in the purchase palendar, the action date is moved back to the first working day. The vendor lead time and purchase calendar are used for all purchase orders, including those created by the Critical Materials process in production management, is set on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form. ==Manufacturing Lead Times== In both MRP and production management, you can choose to use fixed or variable lead times. When using fixed lead times, you must specify a work calendar to use so that dates will only fall on a working day. If you use variable lead times, then both will use the routing operation times in hours to calculate the planned starting and ending dates. With fixed lead times used for production orders, all operations will start or end on the corresponding start or end dates for the production order. Operation lead times include the following elements: *''Queue'': This is the fixed wait time in hours before an operation can start. Typically, you would use this as an allowance for printing paperwork (drawings, work instructions), pulling parts from the stock room, issuing parts, and obtaining tooling and jigs. *:((({S:Warn}Currently this element is not used. ))) *''Setup Time'': This is a fixed time element for setting up the operation. *''Run Time'': The time is multiplied by the remaining quantity to produce and is used when the work center '''Basis for Capacity''' is set to ''Crew Size''. *''Machine Time'': The time is multiplied by the remaining quantity to produce and is used when the work center '''Basis for Capacity''' is set to ''Machines''. *''Move'': This is a fixed element after operation completes before it is available at the next operation. The default move time is set in production preferences but it can be changed in production details. *:((({S:Warn}Currently this element is not used. )))
The operation times are calculated and converted to days, hours, and minutes as follows:{br}
{{{{Set Up Hours + ((Qty to Produce * Run Time) / Run Units) }}}}{br}
{{{{Set Up Hours + ((Qty to Produce * Machine Time) / Machine Units) }}}}{br}
If ''Run Units'' or ''Machine Units'' are zero, then the hours are zero.{br}
The work calendar hours for each work center are then used to calculate the operation start and end dates based solely the number of hours required in each work center. An internal timer is used to determine the relative time at each operation as follows: *Capacity is assumed to infinite *''Crew Size'' and ''Number of Machines'' are not used. *'''Work Center Efficiency''' is not used *Only the total working hours in a work center; that is, if the work hours are 8 am to 5pm with an unpaid break time of 1 hour, then 8 hours are available that day regardless of the time of day. *Only the first row from the '''Work Center Shifts''' tab is used
==Example== Assume the production order starts on Monday and there are 8 working hours in each work center Monday through Friday. The order has three operations and the total fixed and variable time for each operation is 6 hours. *Operation 1 starts on 00:00 relative time on Monday and completes at 06:00 on Monday. *Operation 2 starts at 06:00 relative time on Monday and consumes the remaining 2 hours for today and runs from 00:00 to 04:00 relative time on Tuesday. *Operation 3 starts at 04:00 relative time on Tuesday and consumes the remaining 4 hours available that day and runs on Wednesday 00:00 to 02:00.
If the order started on a Friday and Saturday and Sunday are non-working days, then the Operation would not complete until the next Monday.

The costing of item you make is more complex and detailed than items you buy. You not only have the cost of the materials bought to make an item but also the cost of labor, factory overhead, machinery and/or tooling used in production. And there may be sub-assemblies produced and stored that are input to final assembly of the finished goods items you sell.{br}
Manufacturing costings starts with defining the labor rates for each work center, labor cost rates for production employees if labor is to be entered, overhead rates and application methods, rates for machines and tools used in production. These costs are defined in the Bill of Material module which is the foundation for all other manufacturing modules.{br}
When you create a bill of material you are also creating the planned or standard cost of the item being produced. Once the bill of material is complete, and the bills for any sub-assemblies needed for the final assembly, a cost roll process on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_80_00|Cost Roll] ([~/?ScreenId=AM508000|AM508000]) form is used to roll up these costs. *If the valuation method for the item is ''Standard'', you can update the pending cost of the item and then use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_20_00|Update Standard Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=IN502000|IN502000]) form to apply the new cost. *When a production order is created, the cost roll is again used to create the planned production costs. *When production transactions are entered, a cost is applied and posted to the work in process account. *When production is completed, a costing production receipt is calculated for the value of inventory received. For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PM_ProdOrdCosting|Costing Production Receipts].
==Cost Elements Used in Manufacturing== Costs are broken down into the following on bills of materials, estimates, and production orders: *'''Materials''': The value of the components used to make the stock item. These can be both stock items and non-stock items. For stock items the planned cost is obtained from the '''Price/Cost''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. For production transactions the actual cost is updated when the inventory issue transaction is processed and released. *'''Labor''': The value of labor issued or planned to be issued to make the stock item. Planned labor is calculated based on the run units, run time, and work center standard cost. Actual labor is either calculated based on the work center standard cost or the employee cost rate. If labor is backflushed, the time is calculated automatically based on the quantity reported and costed using the work center standard cost. **'''Fixed Labor:''' if the cost of setup for an operation. Setup is always posted to actual costs when the first quantity is reported for an operation **'''Variable Labor:''' This is the costs calculated for run units and times *'''Overhead:''' The value of overhead rates applied to operations and materials. For actual overhead, it is applied only when a quantity is reported for an operation. **'''Fixed Overhead:''' This represents an amount charged regardless of lot or order size. The the overhead type is ''Fixed'' ** '''Variable Overhead:''' This represents overhead calculated on the basis of labor, machines, or quantity. *'''Subcontract:''' This represent the cost of materials provided to and purchased from a vendor for performing the work. *'''Machine:''' This is the cost of running a machine for an operation. *'''Tools:''' This is the cost of tools consumed at an operation.

You may have a need to have some or all of your production processes contracted out to vendors. If could be for a process that you cannot perform in house such as plating or heat treating. You could use a contract manufacturer or subcontractor when your own capacity is not available or if the contractor does repacking operations for you such as creating variety or gifts packs from multiple products. In some industries, contract manufacturing is pretty common: circuit boards; food and beverage; pharmaceuticals, nutraceuticals, and cosmetics; or aerospace and defense.{br}{TOC} ==Determining Your Needs== These are some of the questions to ponder: #Do the contractors hold inventory for you? #How will you determine when or if to replenish the inventory at the contractor(s)? #Will you be supplying some of the components? ##By transferring from your inventory? ##By placing purchase orders with delivery to the contractor? #Are services included in the purchase price of the product received by you or are there separate charges for product and labor? #What visibility do you need for work being performed by the contractor?
For the purposes of this article we will use the term ''contractor'' to refer to someone who is performing production work on your behalf and the term ''vendor'' when referring to someone you buy from for any materials you supply to the contractor. Of course, the contractor is a vendor also since you are buying services or product from them. ==Inventory Visibility and Replenishment== If you are supplying components, either by transferring from your inventory or by purchasing to the contractor location, you can create a warehouse for contractor or use a warehouse location. Regardless a transfer or purchase receipt will need to be performed to update the on hand balances. If you are sending out items to be processed (such as painting or coating) then you may opt to track them using the production order.{br}
'''Warehouse Location'''{br}
All inventory in warehouse locations is considered as on hand for availability, inventory replenishment, and/or MRP calculations unless excluded. This may not be an issue if component inventory is only held at the contractor.{br}
If you create a purchase order to replenish inventory at the contractor you will need to ensure that you specify the correct warehouse location for the purchase receipt when notified.{br}
For transfers within a warehouse only one-step transfer types are allowed. There is no tracking of the in transit inventory. This may not be an issue with contractors nearby your location.{br}
You can use the standard inventory inquiries and reports to view the inventory by location within a warehouse.{br}
'''Separate Warehouse'''{br}
A separate warehouse may offer greater flexibility in some ways. You can use the inventory one-step transfer but you may also use the inventory two-step transfer if tracking the in transit inventory is desired. Additionally, a separate warehouse allows you to use a Sales Order transfer order type. The transfer order moves through the same processes as sales orders to prepare shipments and shipment paperwork, including carrier labels, and to collect freight/landed costs.{br}
With a separate warehouse you can use Inventory Replenishment and/or MRP to maintain any desired inventory levels at the contractor warehouse. You can also decide to exclude this warehouse completely from MRP.{br}
'''Tracking Inventory Using Production Orders'''{br}
If you are purchasing a service to perform an operation on material you supply for each production order (for example, sending out an item to be powder coated) it may suffice to track the status using a production order. You would issue the materials from your inventory to the production order. The production order operation indicates the inventory issued, the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form would show the inventory issued under the '''Work in Process''' column, and the production order holds the materials issued value.((({S:Hint}Vendor shipments created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_00_00|Vendor Shipments] (AM31000) form can be used to transfer the production item and the components you are supplying to the vendor without having to create a separate warehouse or warehouse location. If you do stock items at a vendor warehouse in advance of production then a separate warehouse or stock location is recommended. ))) ==Stock and Non-Stock Items== You would create an inventory item to recognize the cost of an item being produced and returned to you. For example, the contractor is filling containers you have supplied with materials they supply; you will be billed for the cost of the materials in the container and labor applied to create the product. Remember that the cost of vendor supplied materials should reflect the added value and not include the cost of materials you provided; those materials costs are recognized when you issue them to the production order.{br}
The inventory item would be used to purchase the service and its receipt would serve as a signal to complete the operation. You can use a stock or non-stock inventory item for the services cost.{br}
'''Stock Item'''{br}
The advantages of using a stock item are the following:[anchor|#_66bb504c-0fb9-4d05-a388-e4d6743dcb40] *Purchase orders for a stock item are allocated to the production order and are changed to stock allocations when received. The [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_55_00|Unreleased Material Allocations] ([~/?ScreenId=AM305500|AM305500]) form can be used to issue the allocated stock items. *Stock item can use any valuation method and may better reflect the purchase cost of the service. *Stock items can be planned by MRP. *Transport costs can be applied to the unit costs of services received.
'''Non-Stock Inventory Item'''{br}
You can also create a non-stock item to recognize costs for services that are separately billed or when services are the only charge. Non-stock inventory items can only use standard cost valuation. You can use a different non-stock item for each contractor service charge or use the same item for each service charge. If you use the same item set the standard cost equal to 1.00 and use the quantity required column on the bill of materials for the contractor amount. For example, the contractor charges .53 per piece for one item and 1.23 for another; you would set the quantity required to .53 and 1.23 respectively. Non-stock items cannot be allocated to a production order and must be issued or backflushed in order to post the cost at standard cost. You can decide if a purchase order receipt is required for the non-stock item or not. Requiring a receipt allows the matching of the receipt to the vendor bill. ==Generated Transactions for Non-Stock Items Used for Services== If you use non-stock items for materials used in outside processing, and according to business processes of your organization costs of these items must be accrued, you select the '''Accrue Cost''' check box on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. With this check box selected and when the '''Require Receipt''' check box is selected on the '''General Settings''' tab of the same form, the system posts costs of materials when receiving the items to the warehouse of your organization and releasing a production order to the Expense Accrual account. Transactions generated on the inventory receipt release are listed in the following table.[anchor|#_1d4d0ee5-24fb-4f5b-9f37-f6bcd9723a1c] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="30%" ! Account !width="23%" ! Source of Account !width="23%" ! Debit !width="23%" ! Credit |- | Expense Accrual account | Item | Amount | 0.00 |- | PO Accrual account | Item | 0.00 | Amount |} If the '''Accrue Cost''' check box is selected on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab and the '''Require Receipt''' check box is cleared on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form for the non-stock item used for outside services, then you create the AP bill with this non-stock item. When you release the AP bill, the transactions listed in the following table are generated.[anchor|#_4b03581e-57fb-4b8d-9b37-93c643e99407] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="30%" ! Account !width="23%" ! Source of Account !width="23%" ! Debit !width="23%" ! Credit |- | Expense account | Item | Amount | 0.00 |- | AP account | Item | 0.00 | Amount |} When you issue or backflush the non-stock item for a production order, transactions listed in the following table are generated.[anchor|#_9de972d3-9a1a-4979-8791-2b7cf367f235] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="30%" ! Account !width="23%" ! Source of Account !width="23%" ! Debit !width="23%" ! Credit |- | Work in Process account | Item | Amount | 0.00 |- | Expense Accrual account | Item | 0.00 | Amount |} If the '''Accrue Cost''' check box is cleared on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form, the amounts are posted to the Expense account instead of the Expense Accrual account.((({S:Warn}In the previous versions of Acumatica ERP Manufacturing Edition, we recommended that when using non-stock items for materials in outside processing you specify the same account for the Expense Accrual GL account and Expense GL account. This ensured the proper accounting. By using the same account for both the expense and accrual the amounts will offset; the Work in Process account specified in the production order will hold the expense of outside services to include in the product cost. ))) ==Bills of Material== Because you can have more than one bill of material for a stock item, you can have a bill for in-house production and a different bill for the contractor.{br}
'''Work Centers'''{br}
Typically, you would want to post the contractor costs to the production order by issuing the inventory item. With the work center for the contractor(s) you can apply additional costs not covered by the purchase order such as overhead.{br}
When creating the work center, you should set the Standard Cost to zero so as not to add labor costs when reporting operation completions. The setup time can be use to indicate a fixed time required for the subcontract operation or if the time varies, use the run time.{br}
'''Backflushing'''{br}
Unless you need to do specific issues of lots or serial numbers, we would recommend backflushing the materials consumed or produced by the contractor. If you are using a stock inventory item for the service cost, process the purchase order receipt before issuing or backflushing the material to update the average or FIFO cost. If you are using a non-stock item and the services cost is different than planned, issue the non-stock item for the quantity needed to reflect the cost. ==Set Up Outside Process== The enhanced outside process features can be used with both bills of material and estimates. DO the following to set up the outside process: #On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_10_10|Numbering Sequences] ([~/?ScreenId=CS201010|CS201010]) form, create a numbering sequence] to use for vendor shipments and enter it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form. On the same form you can specify settings for processing vendor shipments in the '''Vendor Shipment Settings''' section. #On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form, create or modify work centers and select the '''Outside Process''' check box. The '''Mass Update''' button on the '''Where Used''' tab can be used to select or clear the '''Outside Process''' check box for some or all bills of material operations using the work center. However, it cannot update the material lines. #Add stock items or non-stock items you will use to pay the vendor for their services. #On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]) form, create or modify the bill of material for the item being produced for each material used for the outsource operation as follows: ##Select the '''Material Type''' of ''Subcontract'' and enter the appropriate '''Subcontract Source'''. ##Enter the appropriate vendor information on the '''Outside Process''' tab of the operation. ##Specify the warehouse if different from the bill of material warehouse from which you will issue the ''Ship to Vendor'' materials. #If you have an existing production created before step 2, you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) from to setup the outside process operations.
==Process Flow== The process flow is the following: #Create a the production order in either of the following forms: #*[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) #*[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_00_00|MRP Display] ([~/?ScreenId=AM400000|AM400000]) #*[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) #*[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_51_00_00|Create Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM510000|AM510000]) #Create the purchase order to pay the vendor for the service. You can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_50_50_00|Create Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO505000|PO505000]) form to create one or more purchase orders for one or more production orders, the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_10_00|Critical Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM401000|AM401000]) form, or the '''Create PO''' action on the '''Outside Process''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form for a single production order and purchase order. Any of these methods create an allocation from the purchase order to the production order. You can view the created purchase by clicking the '''Allocations''' button for the material line on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] form. #Release the production order by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_00_00|Release Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM500000|AM500000]) form. #Issue any materials required for the operations you perform prior to the outside process step that are not marked for backflush from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] form or by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form. #Enter any required move or labor transactions you perform in house prior to the outside process step on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) forms . #Enter the vendor shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_00_00|Vendor Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=AM310000|AM310000]) form. #Print the pick list by using the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\AM_64_40_00|Vendor Shipment Pick List] ([~/?ScreenId=AM644000|AM644000]) report. #Enter any required lot or serial numbers for the production item and materials and confirm the vendor shipment. This will issue the ''Ship to Vendor'' materials and update the subcontract actual cost. #On the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\AM_64_20_00|Vendor Shipment Packing List] ([~/?ScreenId=AM642000|AM642000]) form, print the pick lists that will accompany the items being sent to vendor. #Receive the purchase order used to pay the vendor for the outside service. This will update the subcontract actual cost with the actual purchase cost. #Issue any materials needed for the remaining operations #Complete the remaining operations for the production order using Move or Labor transactions. #Review the production order variances and resolve any discrepancies #Close the production order individually or by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_60_00|Close Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM506000|AM506000]) form.
==Additional Materials== *[https://www.acumatica.com/blog/technical-tuesday-controlling-inventory-inside-external-manufacturing-processes|Technical Tuesday: Controlling Inventory Inside External Manufacturing Processes]

A planning bill of material, sometimes referred to as a ''Pseudo Bill'', is a grouping of operations and materials used in MRP for planning purposes. They are defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]) form exactly the same way as a production bill. You can choose to designate any bill of material for an item as the planning bill or create a new unique bill. If you do not have a planning bill, then the default bill of material is used for planning. There are no restrictions on using the same bill of material as both the default and planning bill.{br}{TOC} ==Why Use a Planning Bill?== Planning bills are most often used to help forecast or master schedule products that have many options where the final configuration is not determined until an order is received. Usually, a planning bill flattens out the multiple level bill of material to a single level bill; that is, the subassembly bills are removed and their key components made components of the planning bill. Alternatively, you could create a planning stock item and construct a planning bill with its components the actual items you sell making each component a phantom if you only want to see their components in MRP and not the assembly.{br}
A manufacturer of desktop computers may have multiple product lines with hundreds of combination of options for processors, memory, storage, monitors, etc. Some of the options may be available across multiple product lines. In order to compress the order to ship lead time, it is desirable to have the components already in stock. Rather than attempt to forecast each product model for every variant, it more feasible to create a pseudo inventory item that will never be sold and construct a planning bill of material with the component options expressed in quantities represented by their past usage.{br}
For example, each desktop computer model can have a 500GB or 1TB capacity disk drive and 60% of the customer select the 1TB disk drive. A planning bill could look like this: ===Planning Bill of Material for All Desktop Computers=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !'''Component''' ! '''Quantity Required''' |- | DiskDrive-1TB | .6 |- | DiskDrive-500GB | .4 |} You would create a forecast or MPS for the planning stock item to drive out the requirements to make or purchase the disk drives. Similarly, you would add other components to the planning bills in their percentages. ==Managing MRP with Planning Bills== It&rsquo;s important to consider that both the planning item and stock items are driving down component demand. The planning bill is intended to represent anticipated sales in the future so as to make or buy the necessary components in a timely manner. When you enter the sales orders or production orders for the items to be sold, they will drive component demand also. *As customer orders are received, you should reduce the forecast or MPS for the planning item so as not to overstate the component demand. You can use the Planning Horizon setting in MRP Preferences to specify when to ignore forecasts and use just actual demand. For example, you expect customers to typically place orders 2 weeks in advance of anticipated ship dates; therefore, you would set the forecast '''Planning Horizon''' or MPS '''Time Fence''' to 14 days. *You should review the actual component usage and periodically adjust their percentages in the planning bill.

