Attributes created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_50_00|Attributes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS205000|CS205000]) form are used for multiple purposes in Acumatica ERP. In many cases they eliminate for customizing forms and when attached to a record, for example, a stock item record, they are automatically available for use in inquiries. You can use attributes in manufacturing forms as well. ==Using Attributes in Bills of Material and Production Orders == Attributes can be attached to bills of material header and/or operations and are copied onto the production order when the order is created. Attributes can be specified for each production order type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form. Attributes can also be added to a production order manually by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form.{br}
Attributes created at the BOM level become order level attributes for the production order. If an order level attribute is enabled for data entry it is available when reporting all operations of the production order. For example, you could create a required attribute for a quality control check for all operations or to record a process value.{br}
If enabled attribute values can be entered for the production order and operation when you enter a move or labor transaction by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_PM_ProdAttributes|Production Attribute Entry] form. If an attribute is marked as ''Transaction Required'', it must be entered. The attribute values entered during production reporting are specific to the transaction. ==Using Attributes in Product Configurator== Attributes have the following purposes in the product configurator:[anchor|#_f5590dce-4151-41bd-850e-0a5983cdc233] *They can be used to collect data used in formulas to calculate the quantity required for an option. For example, calculating the quantity required based on an attribute value for length. *They can be used to capture a value used in production. For example, the text for printing or engraving on a custom piece. *They can be used to with rules to include or exclude features and options.
Attributes and their values used on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_60_00|Configuration Entry] ([~/?ScreenId=AM306000|AM306000]) form are copied to the production order created as view only.

This features provides the ability to have work centers automatically substituted during production order creation based on the warehouse used for production. It can eliminate the need to have warehouse specific bills of material. A company may have multiple production facilities where an item can be made. The components use to make the end item are the same, although they may have different costs, and the production process is the same but the production facilities have different labor and overhead rates.{br}

To use this feature, you must have the ''Multiple Warehouse'' feature enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.
==Substituting Work Centers==
The substitution of work centers is controlled by the '''Substitute Work Centers''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form. Substitutes for each work center are defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form.{br}

If the order type allows substitute work centers, then during production order creation or change of warehouse, and the order is in a planned status the process will look at the current work centers. If the current work center warehouse used for the production order does not match the warehouse for the production order the substitute logic will try to find a substitute from the work center substitute work centers tab were the warehouse on the substitute tab matches the current production warehouse.{br}

When substituted the work center description can replace the operation description based on the setting on the work center.{br}

The backflush labor setting and any work center overheads are copied to the production order during this process.

The Bills of Material part of the Acumatica ERP Manufacturing edition is the foundation for all of the other parts of the edition. A ''bill of material'', or product structure, is a list of the production operations required to build a single level assembly or subassembly. Bills of material become hierarchical when a subassembly is used as a component in another assembly or subassembly. The complete structure, from finished goods down through each subassembly down to raw materials, is referred to a multilevel bill of material.{br}

For each operation in a bill of material you specify the operation times (queue, setup, labor, machine, and move), the materials or components required, the machines available to use, and any tooling. Each element of a bill of material has an associated cost and these cost elements are rolled up level by level to calculate the total cost of the finished good. The rolled up cost becomes the standard or planned cost to produce an item.{br}

In the topics describing bills of material, you create work centers, work calendars, shifts, labor codes, overhead rates, machine, and tools. A work center has a defined capacity which is used by scheduling processes in the Material Requirements Planning and Production Management parts of Manufacturing edition to determine when an operation must be started and when it will be completed and when the materials will need to be issued.{br}

This chapter contains all the information you need to configure and use the bills of material in Acumatica ERP.

The Bills of Material part is the building blocks of the manufacturing software. It is where the operations and work centers are defined, along with materials, steps, overhead, and tools and/or machines. This is where the production order needs can be defined for your inventory items to become that finished good.{br}
What this section will cover:[anchor|#_62a433d5-bb18-44c0-aee7-daa92156ace2] *We will discuss the key features of the Bills of Material part. *Relationship to other Acumatica ERP functional areas {br}{TOC} ==Key Features==[anchor|#_082b32f7-98f9-4482-b9a0-9b419022df99] *BOM / Routing Maintenance: The BOM / Routing provides the ability to directly update the bills of material and routing information by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]) form. *Planning Bills of Material: This process facilitates the forecast, or master production schedule, of product families and/or to order assemblies where the specific configuration is not known until you receive the customer order. For details, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PlanningBills|Planning Bills of Material]. *Activity Based Costing: The system provides a means to provide detailed costing well beyond the cost of the raw materials and labor. Tools costs can be consumed based on usage setup through the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_55_00|Tools] ([~/?ScreenId=AM205500|AM205500]) form. User-defined overhead costs can be setup through the [https://help-2020r1.acumatica.com/(W(9))/Wiki/ShowWiki|Overhead] (AM202500) form. These costs can be accrued at a fixed rate, by labor hour and by the quantity completed. The overhead costs can be associated to a specific product (BOM / routing) or they can be tied to a work center. You are not limited to a finite number of overhead IDs. The user can set up as many or as few as they want. *Alternate BOM / Routing: Too often in manufacturing systems, the systems will only support a single bill of material for a finished good product. To setup alternate bills of material, you often had to set up multiple inventory items. Manufacturing edition provides you with the ability to set up a single finished good item (or subassembly) and create alternate BOMs and routings for that same product. A good use of this is in a situation where the manufacturer has multiple sites. However, they make the same product at the sites. All too often, the different sites have different machinery, work centers, shifts, costs, etc. The system allows you to set up a specific bill of material / routing for each site. *Backflushing: The production transactions can backflush labor and materials and is controlled by the bills of material. By selecting the operations and materials that need to be backflushed this provides the user more control in how and what is being costed. *:((({S:Warn}The system will backflush lot- and serial-tracked items based on the usage parameters. ))) *By-Products Support: By-products are entered as negative materials on the BOM. These materials will be received into inventory at the cost specified on the BOM or at the standard cost if that is what is being used. By-products can be setup to backflush automatically or can be received by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_30_00|Release AM Documents] ([~/?ScreenId=AM503000|AM503000]) forms. *Phantoms: ''Phantom'' items can be entered on the BOM. They are referred to as phantoms because they show up on the BOM but disappear when a production order is created. Only manufactured items with a BOM can become phantoms. *:Several advantages to phantoms in the system include the following: **Ability to be a true phantom or subassembly **Phantoms can be stocked **Multilevel phantoms are supported **Changes to a phantom such as components or quantities when made at the BOM level are carried through the system *Production Steps: Specific steps can be defined at the operation level. Steps are the instructions of what needs to be done for the operation. This allows for full documentation when added with any additional notes of the production process. *Revision Tracking: A complete revision history of a BOM can be maintained. Multiple revisions can be saved to the revision history tables which provides the ability for the information from the past production BOM to be referenced instead of the most current revision. *Shifts: Multiple shift operations are supported through this application through the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_50_00|Shifts] ([~/?ScreenId=AM205000|AM205000]) form. You can create as many shifts as is needed together with the following information: **Work centers that are available **Number of people or machines **Efficiency factors **Working times by shift **Shift differential
