In this topic, you will find answers to the frequently asked questions about bills of material.{br}{TOC}
==How do I set up inventory items to be able to use a bill of material?==
The parent item must be a stock item. Materials, aka components, can be stock or non-stock.
==What should I use for the BOM ID?==
The BOM ID can be up to 15 characters. The numbering sequence specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_10_00|BOM Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM101000|AM101000]) form defines the format of the BOM ID. As with all numbering sequences in Acumatica ERP, you may have different sequences by branch. You may choose auto-numbering or manual entry. Some may prefer to use the inventory id as the BOM ID when the inventory ID is less than 15 characters.((({S:Hint}When importing bills of material, generate a sequence in your import data to reflect the format of the ''BOM ID'' and check the ''Manual Numbering'' box in the numbering sequence. Prior to 2018R2, also uncheck '''Track Revision History''' in BOM Preferences. This way if you find a bill to be incorrect you can simply delete it and reimport using the same ''BOM ID'', otherwise it will assign a new number. With Track Revision History checked, bills of materials are not physically deleted; the end date is set to today instead. For 2018R2, a bill of material revision can be deleted as long as it&rsquo;s not referenced.
)))
==How many bills of material can an inventory item have?==
As many as you want but only one can be the default bill of material specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form for the item–warehouse pair. If you desire to have multiple bills of material for a warehouse because of alternate production methods, you might consider using manual numbering and use a suffix to indicate the alternate.{br}

You can also have multiple active revisions for a bill of material.
==How should I number the operations?==
You should provide for the insertion of new operations. They are sorted as text and not numbers; such as 00030, 020, 10 not 10, 020, 00030. Tips for creating operation numbers are the following:[anchor|#_eae1caac-cda6-4929-93ce-800092d8aea4]
*Do not use leading spaces
*Typically, a sequence of 010, 020, or 100, 110 or 0010, 0020, 0100 are used.
((({S:Hint}The operation numbers are regenerated when a production order is created from the bill to provide for the insertion of operations for a phantom. The numbering starts with 0010 and increments by 10.
)))
Operation numbers may be changed at any time.
==Where do the unit costs for materials in a bill come from?==
The [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form is the source for the cost when you add an inventory item to a bill or production order. The cost used is dependent on the item's valuation method. Unit costs can be manually entered or updated by the cost roll process on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_80_00|Cost Roll] ([~/?ScreenId=AM508000|AM508000]) form. When you add a new material the unit cost defaults from the settings of the item–warehouse pair according to the item's valuation method as follows:[anchor|#_a0efbca1-9503-488e-946b-333cb49edfa0]
*Average or FIFO: Average cost
*:((({S:Warn}If the average cost is zero, then the last cost is used.
)))
*Standard: Standard cost
*Specific: Last cost

For existing materials, the cost roll process can be used to update the unit costs if desired. When production orders are created, the cost roll process obtains the current cost for materials.
==How does the Cost Roll Process Calculate Costs?==
'''Labor for Each Operation'''{br}

((Setup time / lot size) + Run time converted to hours per piece) &#42; (Work Center Standard Cost){br}

'''Materials'''[anchor|#_4069f0be-0e87-4c33-9759-8626b530030d]
*If ''Batch Size'' is zero (0) then ''Qty Required'' &#42; (1 + ''Scrap Factor'')
*If ''Batch Size'' is not zero (0) then Qty Required &#42; (1 + ''Scrap Factor'') &#42; (''Lot Size'' / ''Batch Size'')
*:((({S:Warn}The system copies ''Lot Size'' from the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. If the lot size is zero then ''Min Order Qty'' is used. If both are zero then a lot size of 1 is used.
)))

In all cases, the quantity will be rounded up if the ''Quantity Round Up'' is selected on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form.{br}

Additional details can be found in [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_BATCHSIZES|How Batch Sizes and Quantity Round Up are Used].{br}

'''Machine for Each Operation'''{br}

(Machine hours converted to hours per piece) &#42; (machine standard cost){br}

'''Tools for Each Operation'''{br}

Quantity required &#42; Unit Cost{br}

'''Overhead'''{br}

Overhead is calculated dependent on the overhead type.

The cost roll process, performed by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_80_00|Cost Roll] ([~/?ScreenId=AM508000|AM508000]) form, is used to update the cost of assemblies. When assemblies use the ''Standard'' inventory valuation method, after the process completes, you can use the process to update the pending cost for all or selected assemblies. Before performing the cost roll process, you should review the pending or standard cost of any purchased items with the ''Standard'' valuation method that are used in bills of material.{br}

Typically, standard costs are updated on an annual basis but they can be updated at any time. In this topic, you will read about processes related to updating standard costs of items used in bills of material.
==Updating Pending Standard Costs of Purchased Components==
Before you roll up the costs of assemblies, you need to update the costs of components used in their bills of material. The is no automated process to do this but you can create a Generic Inquiry to export the purchase order history to analyze and calculate a new cost that could be imported to update the pending costs. The [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_Tables|Using Manufacturing Data in Inquiries and Reports] topic lists the DACs or tables used by the manufacturing forms if you just want to select only items used in a bill.{br}

You can also update the pending cost for a item using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form.
==Previewing Cost Changes==
If you wish to review the component cost changes, before updating their standard costs, run the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_75_00|Standard Cost Change Preview] ([~/?ScreenId=IN617500|IN617500]) report.
==Rolling Up the Assembly Costs==
You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_80_00|Cost Roll] ([~/?ScreenId=AM508000|AM508000]) form with level set to ''Multi''. You make sure to check the appropriate options to '''Include Fixed Costs''' and '''Include Material Scrap Factors''' if they are used. When the cost roll is completed, on the form toolbar, click '''Update Pending'''to update the pending costs for all assemblies.{br}

You can select the '''Use Pending Standard for Purchased Items''' check box if you have not yet update your standard cost for components. This will use the component pending costs instead of their standard costs.{br}

You can perform the cost roll and update pending multiple times.
==Updating Standard Costs==
The process of updating standard costs for inventory items, which is run on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_20_00|Update Standard Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=IN502000|IN502000]), moves the pending cost to the standard cost and zeros out the pending cost. The process creates an adjustment batch on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_30_00|Adjustments] ([~/?ScreenId=IN303000|IN303000]) form to update the Inventory and Standard Cost Revaluation GL accounts.{br}

Inventory is always revalued when you run the update standard costs process. However, you might want to revalue inventory without updating the current costs of the items to the next pending cost. In this case, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_20_00|Update Standard Costs] form, you can select the '''Revalue Inventory''' check box. With the check box selected, the form shows all the standard items that have cost layers at the warehouse selected in the '''Warehouse''' box. If you run the update process, inventory will be revalued with the current cost, but the current cost will not be updated with the pending cost for the processed items.

Before you start creating and using bills of material (BOM) in the system, you specify bill of material settings to fit your business needs, as described in this topic. You can at any time adjust the settings as your business grows and changes.{br}
