The art of balancing supply and demand is critical to any manufacturing organization. Forms of the Material Requirements Planning (MRP) part provide powerful planning tools that enables your organization to satisfy customer requirements, while maintaining optimal inventory levels.[anchor|#_fd1bc67b-1f10-43ea-bc3f-6babbe78cb94][anchor|#_2f58fdeb-2629-4435-92ee-42c2416f1423][image:UserGuide/Images/MRP_Chart.png|popup|Material Requirements Planning|450px]{br}
In the part:[anchor|#_d71d027c-3eaa-4f57-bfe6-c328a709c91a] *Sales activities, Master Production Schedules (MPS), and forecasts can be viewed in one centralized location *Flexible selection criteria for creation of purchase and/or production orders *Provides recommendations to manage changes to firm production and/or purchase orders
What this topic will cover:[anchor|#_3b6489d5-6a5b-467f-99aa-54bba674364d] *We will discuss the key features of MRP *We will review the core MRP process and how it works and what it does *Relationship to other Acumatica ERP modules {br}{TOC} ==Key Features==[anchor|#_d6a40bf1-dcbe-4ebd-bcac-485cf33bf1d5] *Full Regeneration (FRG) **A FRG can be scheduled to run in the middle of the night when most of the office personnel are not in the office. The FRG wipes out all the existing MRP data and pulls all the data in from across the system. It then replans what materials are required either to be produced or purchased. **In Acumatica ERP, you can set up automated processing for most processing forms instead of initiating the processing manually. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Scheduled_Processing|Scheduled Processing]. *Suggested Replenishment Orders **MRP generates planned orders to balance demand with supply. From MRP you convert the planned orders into actual purchase, transfer, and production orders.
==Relationship to Other Functional Areas==[anchor|#_74e5d399-52af-45a9-9756-56552617d3fd] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Area !Usage |- | Inventory &gt; Replenishment Classes | You can create a replenishment class with the replenishment source of ''Manufacturing'' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_88_00|Replenishment Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN208800|IN208800]) form. |- | Inventory &gt; Replenishment Seasonality | The factors used for the seasonality periods can be applied to forecasts by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_20_00|Generate Forecast] ([~/?ScreenId=AM502000|AM502000]) form. |- | Inventory &gt; Replenishment Parameters | Values for safety stock, added lead time, reorder point, and maximum quantity specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) forms are used to calculate the suggested purchase and production orders. |- | Inventory &gt; Warehouses | You can specify for each warehouse the demand and supply options. For example, in forecasts, if all are cleared, as would be the case for a warehouse used for returns or defective material, then items in the warehouse will not be planned. |- | Sales Orders | The promise date of open sales order lines for stock items is used as the demand date. Optionally you can include or exclude sales orders on hold or on credit hold. |- | Purchase Orders | The promise date of open purchase order lines with the ''Goods for Inventory'' type is used as the supply date. Optionally you can include or exclude purchase orders on hold. |- | Bills of Material | The effective date start and end dates of active[HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_80_00|Bill of Material] ([~/?ScreenId=AM208000|AM208000]) determine which one is used to schedule suggested production orders and their material requirements based on the calculated start or end dates.[anchor|#_15b72a51-66a3-45f2-833c-e0c49767db98] *The operation times or fixed lead times are used to forward or backward schedule the suggested production orders. *The effective and expiration dates of each material determine if a material is active on the start date.
|- | Production Orders | The start date of a production order created by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form is the date required for each material; the end date is the supply date for the item being manufactured. Optionally you can include or exclude production orders on hold. |}

This topic addresses the common question about the Material Requirements Planning processes.{br}{TOC} ==When should MRP be run?== Generally, MRP should be run before each business day after all sales and purchase orders have been entered and after all transaction affecting inventory have been posted. Since this is a very resource dependent process, it should be run so as not to conflict with database maintenance processes. ==What is the Difference between the ''MRP Display'' and the ''MRP Exceptions''?==[anchor|#_bb96659f-a72d-4594-9057-4c3b1ade92dd] *On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_00_00|MRP Display] ([~/?ScreenId=AM400000|AM400000]) form, a list of suggested supply orders (aka planned orders) that need to be converted to actual purchase, production, or transfer orders is displayed. *The primary use of MRP exceptions, displayed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_30_00|MRP Exceptions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM403000|AM403000]) form, is to execute the recommended actions on existing actual supply orders to meet requirements. This includes the following: **Expediting or de-exediting existing purchase and production orders to meet demand; **Canceling supply orders that are no longer needed; **Transferring inventory from one warehouse to another to meet demand; **Reviewing sales, purchase, and production orders that on hold and thus ignored by MRP; **As a list of late purchase and production orders.
It is commonly the first thing a planner or buyer will look at, particularly for expedites, before looking at the new planned orders. ==Which Items are planned?== All stock items with the '''MRP Item''' box selected on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. MRP plans at the item–warehouse level; that is, only supply and demand for the stock item and warehouse combination are used. However, if there is a demand for an item and warehouse and there is supply in another warehouse, an MRP exception of the ''Transfer Available'' type is generated on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_30_00|MRP Exceptions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM403000|AM403000]) form.{br}
Stock items with the status of ''Inactive'' or ''Marked for Deletion'' are never planned. ==How does MRP determine which components are used?== For production orders, the materials details with a quantity remaining are always used.{br}
For planned orders the default planning bill and its most recent active revision are used; if a planning bill is not specified, then the default bill is used. For MPS orders, the bill specified on the MPS order is used. Additionally, the ''Effective Start Date'' and ''Effective End Date'' specified for each material line in the specified parent bill of material is used to determine if a component is effective on the planned order or planned operation start date.{br}
For 2019R1, the active bill of material selected is based on the effective dates of the bill revision. For example, if a revision exists for a future start date it will be used for planned orders with a start date on or after this date. It is possible also to have a bill of material effective between a range of dates. ==In what sequence does MRP plan?== MRP plans top down; it uses the bill of material low level code to determine what items to plan first. The first items planned have a low level code of zero. If a planned order is generated for a manufactured item, then a requirement is inserted for each of the stock items components as specified in its default bill of material on the '''Manufacturing''' of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. If there is no planning bill of material specified, then the default bill of material is used.{br}
The process continues down through the low level codes doing the same gross to net calculations at each level. ==What dates does MRP use for supply and demand orders?==[anchor|#_23e0f737-311a-4359-83e7-80ecd577647e] *Sales order line '''Ship On''' date (including transfers). The sales order defaults this as the Requested On date minus the lead days for this customer (delivery settings). *Purchase order line '''Promised '''date *Production order '''End Date''' for supply *Production order '''Start Date''' or operation '''Start Date''' for the materials required. The same logic is used for MPS and MRP planned orders.
==What data does MRP use and what data can be excluded?==[anchor|#_51719b16-f5bc-4fec-a0b5-94f32722796a] *Forecasts *Sales Orders, including open transfer orders *Shipments not released *Inventory On Hand *MPS Orders *Production Orders *Purchase Orders
By specifying preferences on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form, you can decide if sales order on hold, purchase orders on hold, and/or production orders on hold are included or not. An ''Exception Message'' is generated for each order on hold and should be reviewed after running MRP.{br}
You can clear the check boxes above on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form to exclude selected data. If all are cleared, the warehouse is excluded completely. ==How do allocations impact MRP?== The current process of regenerating MRP uses all the allocation details records, as shown on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. It does not matter if the allocation records are included in supply or deducted from demand on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_15_00|Availability Calculation Rules] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201500|IN201500]) because MRP needs to see all supply and demand. There are exceptions:[anchor|#_1c18a2aa-af3b-41b8-9d52-aca3efb23da7] *The settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form for ''Include Orders on Hold'' are used. *Supply and demand for production orders with a status of ''Completed'' are ignored. *Inactive stock items are excluded from planning.
==How is inventory on hand calculated?== For each warehouse, it is the on hand balance of any warehouse location where the '''MRP''' box is selected.((({S:Warn}If the '''MRP''' box is cleared for a warehouse location, then any production orders with this location as the planned receipt location are also excluded from MRP. ))) ==Are non-stock items planned?== No, they are not inventoried. ==How does MRP determine if an item is manufactured or purchased?== The source of an item is specified in the '''Replenishment Source''' box on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. ==How Should Purchased Items be Set Up?== MRP uses settings specified either on the '''Replenishment Info''' tab or on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form depending of whether the ''Inventory Replenishment'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]): If the feature is enabled, then settings specified on the '''Replenishment Info''' tab are used. You can override replenishment settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items]form with the settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. The following settings are used:[anchor|#_9ddb786b-ccbf-49be-b506-6a92d98d483e] *''Safety Stock or Reorder Point'': The value used is determined by the value of ''Stocking Method'' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form. If you have multiple warehouses, you should only set these values on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form.
The vendor details for the default vendor from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form, unless overridden on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] form, are used as follows:[anchor|#_d141e4a7-100f-4a90-9485-a7e45fbeebf5] *''Add Lead Time (Days)'': This is used to adjust the default vendor lead time *''Min. Order Qty'': This becomes the minimum order quantity for the planned orders. *''Lot Size'': The planned orders are rounded up to the nearest multiple of lot size. If demand is 37 and the min is 20 and the lot size is 5, then the planned order quantity will be 40. *''Max. Order Qty'': The planned order quantity cannot be greater than the maximum. Multiple planned orders will be created to cover the demand. ((({S:Warn}If an item does not have a default vendor, then the values are taken from the '''Manufacturing''' tab. ))) ==How are forecasts used?== A forecast, created by using the [https://help-2020r1.acumatica.com/(W(11))/Wiki/ShowWiki|Forecast] (AM202000) form, is due on their start date. If the start date is earlier than the business date plus the '''Planning Horizon''' specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form, the forecast record is updated to clear the '''Active''' box on the forecast record.{br}
If the forecast has the '''Dependent''' box selected, then sales orders with a promise date between the '''Begin Date''' and '''End Date''' of every forecast are automatically reduced by the sales order line open quantity. For example, if the forecast is 200 for 9/1 to 9/30, then all sales orders with a promise dates between 9/1 and 9/30 have a total open quantity of 150, the remaining forecast of 50 is used. ==Are forecasts customer specific?== Yes, you can reference a customer on a forecast and that forecast is only consumed by only sales orders for that customer. You should not mix both customer specific and non-specific forecasts for an inventory item because sales orders for that customer will net against both. You could however increase the non-specific forecast to include the customer specific forecast. ==How are grace days used?== For each demand date, MRP determines if a supply order within the grace days can fully satisfy the demand. The grace days are specified in the '''Grace Period''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form. If the demand is no fully satisfied by supply orders with the grace days, then a planned order is created to satisfy the remaining demand. The following table shown an example of using the grace period.[anchor|#_ec1d2c09-424f-4a2d-bd01-437715c26d33] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !'''Date''' ! '''Demand (-) or Supply (+) Qty''' ! '''Projected On Hand''' |- | October 6th | -10 Production Material | -10 |- | October 10th | -10 Production Material | -20 |- | November 9th | 40 Purchase Order | 20 |} In the above example, if the ''Grace Period'' is '''30''' calendar days, then the purchase order supply due on November 9th only satisfies the demand of October 10th and a planned order will be created to satisfy the demand of October 6th. If the ''Grace Period'' is '''90''' days, then both demands are fully satisfied by the Purchase Order supply and no planned order is created.{br}
The logic does not apply when a supply order due date is earlier than the demand date and it satisfies all demands because there is no need to create a planned order.{br}
You should consider your demand and supply patterns, supply lead times, and minimum order quantities to determine an appropriate value for ''Grace Period''.{br}
Regardless of the Grace Period setting, exceptions messages are always generated to expedite or defer supply orders. The generation of exception messages is controlled by the MRP preferences for '''Days Before''' and '''Days After'''. ==What are suggested values for Days Before and Days After?== First, both values must be less than or equal to the '''Grace Days'''. The greater the values, less exception messages are generated, however reviewing the exception messages helps to ensure that supply orders are will be received in time. You should consider your lead times and if your suppliers, either your own manufacturing or your vendors, can adapt to your new due dates. You have to consider also the number of times you have to ask your suppliers to change their promise dates.[anchor|#_606e0649-5584-4cb0-9c48-d0bdc5c4e458][anchor|#_e76d008f-cec4-4cf9-a90c-65d154cc0501][image:UserGuide/Images/MFG__MRP_Days_Before_and_After.PNG|popup|Selection of a demand require date|300px][anchor|#_65b7056d-f3cc-45f0-ad13-12d1d160821e] *''Days Before'': If most of your lead times are a week or less, then 7 days would be appropriate. You would want your vendor to defer a delivery when demand changes to a later date. If your lead times are larger, then you need to consider how often you want to ask your vendors to adjust their promise dates. *''Days After'': This is the more critical value since a late delivery from a supplier impacts your ability to manufacture and/or ship to customers. A value of 2 to 5 days is suggested.
==How Can I Consolidate Planned Orders?== The ''Group Planning'' number of days provides you with ability to specify how planned orders are grouped for consolidation when you select them on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_00_00|MRP Display] ([~/?ScreenId=AM400000|AM400000]) form. The first planned order selected is the starting date and is assigned a ''Group Nbr'' of 1. Then any planned orders with a required date with the group planning days are assigned the to group 1. The next planned order, for the same item, or planned order for a new item are assigned ''Group Nbr'' of 2.

[anchor|#_2653b7f3-873b-442d-9e03-c7c50536b71e] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Step !width="80%" ! Description |- | Initialization | The first step the FRG performs is an Initialization phase. Certain variables are initialized. A connection is made to the database. Parameters are read from the MRP Setup. |- | Set Low Level Codes | The first step is to set the low level codes of all the Inventory Items. This allows MRP to process the highest level items that may generate demand for the lower items. |- | First Pass | First Pass is the information-gathering phase. The MRP Processor will go out and bring together all the various supplies and demands for inventory.{br}
First Pass first gathers current inventory values, what the current quantity on hand is. The safety stock is removed from this value; MRP treats safety stock as if those quantities were not available.{br}
First Pass then determines where it will get future supplies. This may be Finished Good Items on Open Production Orders or it may Open Purchase Orders. It will then look at demands from Sales Orders, Shippers, and Material Requirements on Purchase Orders.{br}
First Pass will process the Master Planning Schedule (MPS). It first updates the MPS information. Those MPS records that fall outside of the MPS Time Fence are marked as inactive. In addition, existing Production Orders may consume the MPS. The Production Order can consume the MPS even though that Production Order is completed and closed. A Production Order will consume the MPS based on the scheduled End Date of the Production Order. |- | Forecasts | Forecasts are processed as each level is processed. Therefore, if the Forecast is dependent, ALL requirements may consume the Forecast. This allows the user to not only Forecast at the Sales Order level, but also Forecast at Lower Levels. |- | Adjust Quantities | The next step is to reconcile existing supplies with existing demands at each level. If we have a sales order for 100 units and a production order that is making 100 units in time, then MRP does not have to plan anything for that sales order.{br}
The key to this routine is that to remember MRP is extremely date sensitive. In other words, in the above example, if that production order was not going to make those units for another 60 days then MRP does need to plan something else for that sales order so that it ships in time. MRP uses the ''Grace Period'' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_00_00|MRP Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM100000|AM100000]) form to determine if that supply can be used for the current demand. |- | Blowdown | Once all the existing data is reconciled, the Blowdown routine will now plan MRP orders. This routine is looking at all demand items that are not being supplied in time for the level being processed. These are being planned out. If a Reorder Qty is set for an Inventory Item, MRP will plan its orders in multiples of that reorder quantity. If the item is a manufactured item, MRP will explode through its Bill of Material and create more requirements for its materials that will be processed at a lower level.{br}
The key to this phase is to plan accurate Action dates. The system will calculate Cumulative Lead Times so that if a Sales Order needs to ship on March 22nd, that means the Production Order must be created on March 10th. This also means that the Purchase Order for the raw material that we do not have needs to be placed by March 5th. During this phase, MRP is writing all of its requirements to the MRP details table. The details are reviewed by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_00_00|MRP Display] ([~/?ScreenId=AM400000|AM400000]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_30_00|MRP Exceptions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM403000|AM403000]) forms. |- | Completion | Finally, once all of the requirements are planned, all the data is brought together into the MRP plan table. This table is used so you can view all of the requirements for an item using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_40_00|Detail Inquiry] ([~/?ScreenId=AM404000|AM404000]) form{br}
The first section provides brief description of an idea to be detailed in the topic. Usually 3-5 phrases, the last paragraph should clearly list what details are described in the sections of the topic. |}

Both create demand and are planned by MRP. Both are exploded down through their bills of material to create ''dependent ''demand for their components. How are they different? The key difference is the source.[anchor|#_5a2ad6e2-9072-4f84-9f3f-db6365a10eef]
*A forecast predicts future demand (orders) that will be placed by customers. A Forecast is a demand item and sales orders typically consume the forecast.
*The Master Production Schedule (MPS) is a proposed build schedule. It is a planned production schedule that identifies what is being planned to be built in the coming weeks. An MPS can be consumed like a forecast, however an MPS is a planned supply item and it is consumed by a Production Order, a supply item.

When do you use a MPS instead of a Forecast? The answer is whose forecast is it? If it is coming from sales identifying what they expect to ship, use Forecasts. If Production is stating that this is what they need to produce, use the MPS.{br}

Both forecasts and master production schedules are used to build inventory in anticipation of customer orders and drive down through the bills of materials to create dependent demand for the materials required to build the products. Forecasts or master schedules are especially important when the cumulative lead times from raw materials to finished products are longer than your customers are willing to wait. Even in a make to order environment there may be long lead components that must be sourced and stocked in order to meet customer expectation of delivery.{br}

Forecasted demand may be highly seasonal whereas a master production is typically constructed to smooth production; e.g. build stock when demand is low to cover higher demand in future periods. A master production schedule is a statement of production that should take into consideration forecasts, sales order backlog, desired inventory levels, storage constraints, and production resources.{br}{TOC}
==Creating Forecasts==
Forecasts can be generated from historical data by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_20_00|Generate Forecast] ([~/?ScreenId=AM502000|AM502000]) form or manually entered or adjusted using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_20_00|Forecast] ([~/?ScreenId=AM202000|AM202000]) form. When marked as dependent, sales orders reduce or consume the forecast.
==Creating a Master Production Schedule==
You can think of MPS orders as firm planned orders and they are treated the same as production orders in MRP; that is, MRP will generate a defer, expedite, or cancel exception when MPS orders are not in synch with demand. MPS orders are entered using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_10_00|Master Production Schedule] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201000|AM201000]) form. You can create a Production Order from an MPS Order and similar to forecasts, when marked as dependent, creating a production order reduces or consume an MPS Order.
==Safety Stocks and Reorder Points==
Forecasts are inevitably incorrect because of the nature of customer orders. Build schedules may not be executed as planned because of supply or production disruptions. Safety stocks and/or reorder points can be used to buffer demand and supply variability. The [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_85_00|Calculate Replenishment Parameters] ([~/?ScreenId=IN508500|IN508500]) form can be used to calculate safety stocks and reorder point based on the desired service level, seasonality model, and demand forecast model. Generally, you would set a safety stock or reorder point for the finished goods and not at the component level; an exception would be components used as spare or service items. The added safety stock or reorder point for the finished goods drives down into component demand during MRP regeneration on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_50_00|Regenerate MRP] ([~/?ScreenId=AM505000|AM505000]) form.{br}

You should take into consideration demand that triggers MRP replenishment is due on the date the projected on hand balance drops below the safety stock or reorder point and this may not provide sufficient lead time. Additionally, unlike forecasts safety stocks or reorder points are not consumed by sales orders. When possible, a forecast or MPS is a better solution since both represent future demand.

In this topic, you will read about item allocation in production management.{br}

In the following diagram, you can see the general concept of allocating items.[anchor|#_9fbb4398-ce2f-4fb4-b4a2-84e7a39a8dea][anchor|#_376295a1-59f9-40f8-9515-2a054882b07e][image:UserGuide/Images/MfgPlanTypes.png|popup|Allocations for production|350px]{br}{TOC}
==Allocating Purchase Orders to Production Orders==
'''Using Critical Materials Process or Checking Mark for PO'''{br}

When you create purchase orders by using processes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_10_00|Critical Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM401000|AM401000]) or the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_50_50_00|Create Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO505000|PO505000]) form, an allocation is created from the PO to the production material line. The purchase order line created will be ''Goods for MFG'' for stock items or ''Non-Stock for MFG'' for non-stock items. Once the purchase order is created the allocations on the production order materials line are updated. The supply allocation type depends on the status of the purchase order:[anchor|#_2be5e83b-2d29-4cff-b8dd-7ab3e0a6e5c9]
*''Purchase for Prod. Prepared:'' When the purchase order does not have a status of ''Open''.
*''Purchase for Production:'' When the purchase order is status is ''Open''.

Changing the status or changing the hold flag will change the allocation type. The demand for production orders for purchased items is shown as ''Production to Purchase''. When the purchase order is received the demand allocation is updated to ''Production Allocated'' for the quantity received.{br}

'''Using APS Scheduling'''{br}

If the ''Advanced Planned and Scheduling'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, when you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_10_00|Rough Cut Planning] ([~/?ScreenId=AM501000|AM501000]) form to process production orders, available purchase orders will be allocated. The allocation type will be the same as above.((({S:Warn}The line type of the purchase order is not updated when the line is allocated to a production order.
)))
==Allocating Stock Items to Production Orders==
You can manually allocate available items or remove an allocation to a production order by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form. The demand allocation is ''Production Allocated''.((({S:Danger}Currently, you cannot allocate a specific lot- or serial-tracked item.
)))((({S:Warn}Allocations are only removed when the actual quantity issued is equal to the quantity required or when the production order is closed. Completing a production order does not relieve the allocations because the material has not been fully issued. If you need to close a production order short (you were going to make 10 but because of a shortage you could only make 8), then reduce the ''Qty to Produce'' and then close the order.
)))
'''Allocating Production Orders to Sales Orders'''{br}

If the production order is created from the sales order it creates a ''SO to Production'' demand allocation. When the production order is created the supply allocation depends on the status of the production order:[anchor|#_a3750cc7-d8f6-46fb-ba85-e488a13c40f3]
*''Production for SO Prepared:'' The production order has a status of ''Planned'' or has been placed ''On Hold''.
*''Production for SO:'' The production order is has a status of ''Released'' or ''In Process'' and is not ''On Hold''.

When the production move creates an inventory receipt the ''SO to Production'' allocation is decreased and the ''SO Allocated'' increased. If the inventory item is lot or serial tracked, the lot or serial number is allocated to the sales order line.{br}

'''Allocating Production Orders to Other Production Orders'''{br}

When you create linked production orders by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_10_00|Critical Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM401000|AM401000]) form, the subassemblies are allocated as ''Production Allocated''. The supply allocations are dependent on the status of the created production order:[anchor|#_5b074c86-5c60-4b5a-81f6-9f2d8f04ecc0]
*''Production for Prod. Prepared:'' The production order has a status of ''Planned'' or has been placed ''On Hold''.
*''Production for Production:'' The production order is has a status of ''Released'' or ''In Process'' and is not ''On Hold''.

'''MRP and Allocations'''{br}

The process of regenerating MPR performed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_50_00|Regenerate MRP] ([~/?ScreenId=AM505000|AM505000]) form has been modified to use the allocation details for planning regardless of availability calculation rules specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_15_00|Availability Calculation Rules] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201500|IN201500]) form.

This form may be used when issuing or receiving inventory to select or enter locations and/or select/generate lot/serial numbers.{br}
When you click the '''Allocations''' button the Allocation dialog box is opened. ==Allocations Dialog Box== By using this dialog box, you can view how the specified on the line quantity of the item is distributed between locations, subitems, lot or serial numbers or you can generate and assign lot/serial numbers to the specified quantities of the stock item if relevant or you can assign warehouse locations for the specified quantities of the item or assign subitems. Whether lot or serial numbers should be generated when the item is received or used depends on the '''Assignment Method''' option selected for the lot/serial class of the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form.{br}
