When you receive items from a production order by using the labor or move transactions, an inventory receipt is created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]) form to debit the inventory account and subaccount and to credit the work in process (WIP) account/subaccount.[anchor|#_fb18eecd-1495-43f3-a793-ce2addaaf351] *If the stock item being received has a valuation method of ''Standard Cost'', then the receipt cost is quantity received multiplied by the standard cost for the stock item and warehouse. *For ''FIFO'', ''Average'', and ''Specific'' valuation methods, the receipt cost is calculated depending on the costing method selected for the production order.
You can read more about the costing and valuation methods in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods].{br}{TOC} ==Costing Methods== Production orders support two costing methods and the default method for new production orders is defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form. The ''Actual'' method uses only the actual WIP balance to calculate the cost; the ''Estimated'' method combines actual and planned costs to cater to situations where material and labor transactions are not always reported before the inventory is receipted from the production order. ==Actual Costing Method== The calculated unit cost for the manufacturing to inventory transactions, such as inventory receipts, will be the WIP balance divided by the quantity completed, including scrap if the option to include scrap is used. There will be no planned cost estimating calculated into the unit cost of the production receipt. When using this method, the WIP Balance is zeroed after each receipt and there will never be a WIP Balance on the production order when the order is completed. This method may be appropriate when:[anchor|#_9053c4f3-b54a-4d8e-bb3d-f02cbe07d26f] *More or less material is used based on testing the process; for example, add salt to taste or add calcium until the Ph value equals to a particular value. *A different material is added or substituted based on availability or inspection; for example, a repair order when parts need to be replaced. *Labor times are estimated or unknown until the work is performed.
==Actual Cost Examples== '''Example 1'''{br}
Production order to produce 10 units currently has an actual WIP Total of $100 with zero completed units (MFG to Inventory is zero). A user creates a move transaction to complete 5 units into inventory. The total cost for the transaction will be $100 with a calculated unit cost of 100 / 5 = $20 each.{br}
After the move transaction another $70 is added to the production order making the actual WIP Total $170 and a WIP Balance of $70. A user creates a move transaction for the final 5 units. The move transaction is for a total of $70 with a calculated unit cost of 70 / 5 = $14 each. The order is complete with a WIP Total of $170, WIP Balance of zero, and MFG to Inventory of $170.{br}
Receipt cost summary:[anchor|#_64205f07-71e6-47e9-94b0-126bd96aacf8] #$20.00 #$14.00
'''Example 2'''{br}
Production order to produce 10 units currently has an actual WIP Total of $0 with zero completed units (MFG to Inventory is zero). A user creates a move transaction to complete 5 units into inventory. The total cost for the transaction will be $0 with a calculated unit cost of 0 / 5 = $0 each.{br}
After the move transaction the first costs are added to the production order totaling $170 making the WIP Total $170 and a WIP Balance of $170. A user creates a move transaction for the final 5 units. The move transaction is for a total of $170 with a calculated unit cost of 170 / 5 = $34 each. The order is complete with a WIP Total of $170, WIP Balance of zero, and MFG to Inventory of $170.{br}
Receipt cost summary:[anchor|#_87e30ce8-417f-4428-9cfb-5066179f05cf] #$0.00 #$34.00
'''Example 3'''{br}
Production order to produce 10 units currently has an actual WIP Total of $170 with zero completed units (MFG to Inventory is zero). A user creates a move transaction to complete the full 10 units into inventory. The total cost for the transaction will be $170 with a calculated unit cost of 170 / 10 = $17 each. The order is complete with a WIP Total of $170, WIP Balance of zero, and MFG to Inventory of $170.{br}
Receipt Cost Summary[anchor|#_e99bbcff-cbc3-4ac8-a44f-a2c0f801365f] #$170.00 ((({S:Warn}[anchor|#_aad71b60-5785-464f-b0b8-84ef071e70b0] #Accurate costs with the cost method of '''Actual''' therefore are dependent on the reporting of all required transactions before inventory is received from production. Costs are also affected if materials are set to backflush and negative inventory balances are not allowed; the materials that are short will '''NOT''' be issued. Because the receipt costs are calculated based on the WIP balance at the time of the receipt, this may have an undesired impact on your costs when the units are issued or shipped. #Transactions created and processed by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_80_00|WIP Adjustment] ([~/?ScreenId=AM308000|AM308000]) form adjust the WIP balance and will be included in the cost of any receipt posted after the adjustment. ))) Production order variances are still calculated for each cost element in order to provide a means to measure performance. ==Estimated Costing Method== The estimated costing method uses a combination of actual and planned costs. Very often in manufacturing the actual product flows through production processes faster than the transactions to track it are reported. For example, employees might indicate the labor hours and materials used on the production tickets which are then collected at the end of their shift and reviewed by a supervisor who then submits them for data entry. The product may have already been packed, moved into inventory, and shipped before the actual labor and materials have been posted. Without having the actual labor and materials reported the value in WIP is understated and doing a receipt without these costs will result in an understated receipt cost.{br}
In order to minimize the impact of understated costs, the labor and move transactions calculate a receipt cost based on the labor and materials actual hours and quantities plus the difference between and planned and actual labor hours and quantities. Additionally, machine, tooling, and overhead costs are also calculated and applied. The can result in a WIP balance that is only resolved when the production order is financially closed even for stock items using ''FIFO'', ''Average'', or ''Specific Cost'' valuation methods.{br}
If you are using ''Standard Cost'' valuation method for your assemblies, then the receipt cost is always the current standard cost and any rate or usage variances are applied as a WIP Variance when the production order is financially closed. ==Updating Planned Costs== If you are aware of significant labor, material, or other costs changes since the production order was created, you can use the ''Calculate Planned Cost'' action on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form if the order has a status of ''Planned'' or the order is on ''Hold ''and has a status of ''Released'' or ''In-Process''. ==Impact of Using Estimated Costs== There are a few issues with using the combination of planned and actual costs that you need to be aware of. The planned costs are calculated using the current values at the time the production order is created and costs may change. Actual costs are determined at the time the materials, labor, or move batch is released and processed by the system. For example, the cost layer to use for FIFO valuation materials is determined when the Inventory Issue batch is released, not when it is created.{br}
There are other examples of cost differences between planned and actual costs:[anchor|#_ae155664-e4f9-4f1f-8ed6-9b79b05b7792] *A purchase receipt may change the average or last cost of a stock item component or the standard cost has been updated. *Planned Labor is calculated using work center standard rates and you report labor using employee rates that are different. *Rate changes were made work center, overhead, machine and/or tooling after the production order planned costs were calculated.
Differences between the planned unit costs and actual unit costs are considered ''Rate Variances''. Differences between planned quantities and actual quantities are ''Usage Variances''. ==How Does Scrap Affect Cost?== Scrap affects the cost calculations for all valuation methods except Standard Cost. If the '''Include Scrap in Completions''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form, the receipt cost will be divided by the completed units to calculate the unit cost. For example, the production order called for 10 units to be produced, the WIP Balance is $100.00 without any variances, and a receipt of 9 units completed and 1 scrap is entered:[anchor|#_70288b87-d276-43ab-bd7a-d1710dc59a45] *With ''Include Scrap in Completions'' '''checked''', the unit cost is $11.11 ($100.00 / 9 Units completed), the production order status is set to ''Completed'', and WIP is credited for the $100.00. *With ''Include Scrap in Completions'' '''unchecked''', the unit is $10.00 because only 9 units were completed, the production order status remains ''In Process'', and WIP is credited for $90.00.
There is no separate accounting entry generated by reporting scrap, the only impact is how the receipt cost is calculated.{br}
If there are yield variances you can report the difference as a scrap amount if the '''Include Scrap in Completions''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] form. Scrap quantities can be positive (added to quantity completed) or negative (subtracted from quantity completed). For example, if the planned quantity to produce was 500 units but the actual yield was 510 units, you can enter -10 as scrap.((({S:Warn}If you have already expensed the cost of scrap, then total scrap is ignored since the WIP Balance was already reduced by the scrap expense. See [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_Scrap|Handling Production Scrap and Waste] for more information. ))) ==Rate Variances vs. Usage Variances== Rate variances will not create a production order variance, the full value of WIP is credited at production completion if the actual quantity completed equals the quantity to produce. If you do a partial receipt, you may get a different cost for each receipt depending on when labor and material are posted to the production order.{br}
Usage variances, however, can result in a production order variance and WIP balance at completion. Usage variances are created in the following cases:[anchor|#_fd9fb3ae-20ab-4595-8250-a91f9289ffaf] #There is a difference between the planned and actual labor hours. #There is a difference between planned and actual material issue quantities
Any WIP balance for completed production orders is relieved when production orders are (financially) closed which creates a credit or debit to the WIP Variance account. The unit cost of completed items is not changed during the financial close. ==Receipt Cost Calculations== The receipt cost calculation for assemblies having a valuation method other than Standard Cost compares the planned quantities of labor and materials at planned costs to the actual quantities of labor and materials at actual cost. The calculations are performed for each operation and summarized. The cost calculations are not complex but they are very detailed to ensure a representative cost for receipts. They consider not only the actual costs posted but also the costs that should have been posted when an operation or material issue has not been reported.{br}
Before calculating the operation costs, the final operation production quantity (including scrap if configured in production preferences) is used if necessary to adjust prior operation completion quantities if they are less. For example, given this routing and operation 0030 is the last operation and you report a quantity completed of 6:[anchor|#_81c9772a-4e94-44c3-a2d5-6aac3c38262f] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Operation !Actual Completed Quantity !Adjusted Completed Quantity |- | 0010 | 10 | N/A quantity is greater than 0030 |- | 0020 | 4 | 6: The operation actual completion quantity is made equal to the last operation completed quantity, |- | 0030 | 6 | 6 |} ==Labor Cost Calculation== Labor costs are calculated for each operation by using the following formula, if the actual labor hours are less than planned labor hours.{{{{Actual labor amount + (Planned - Actual labor hours) * Work center standard rate }}}} ==Materials Cost Calculation== Material costs are calculated for each material item by using the following formula, if the actual quantity issued is less than the planned quantity to issue.{{{{actual material cost + (planned quantity - actual quantity) * planned unit cost }}}} ==Machine and Tools Cost Calculations== These costs are always backflushed according to the actual quantity completed at each operation or, if necessary, by the adjusted quantity completed. ==Fixed Overhead Cost Calculation== If not already calculated, the fixed overhead is calculated for each operation. ==Variable Overhead Cost Calculation== Similar to labor and materials cost calculations, the variable overhead is calculated according to the actual quantity completed at each operation or, if necessary, by the adjusted quantity completed. ==Updating Production Orders to Recognize All Costs== If labor and/or material usage variances should be included in the production receipt or completion costs and not as a variance, by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form you can update the production order operations and materials planned hours and quantities to be the actual hours and quantities before performing a receipt.

This information is repeated in the form reference topic for the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form.{br}
The purpose of these settings is to assist users in reporting the correct quantities for production transactions.{br}
These settings affect the behavior of the materials, labor, and move transactions and are intended to reduce the possibility of data entry errors.((({S:Warn}If you are using data collection devices and software from a third party you need to make sure they will honor the data entry checks. )))[anchor|#_da15e5d7-2771-45e8-982e-8a581fa4648c] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="33%" ! Setting !width="66%" ! Description |- | '''Under Issue Material''' | This checks if the quantity being reported on a move or labor transaction has enough material issued to cover the quantity. This includes the current and all previous operations. If the Actual material is less than the planned quantity based on the quantity being moved the condition exists. The options for this setting:[anchor|#_0218b261-ba50-40e4-8bba-b70feb04def6] *''Allow:'' No error message is displayed. *''Warn:'' A warning message is displayed only when the batch is saved but the transaction can continue. If the user releases the batch, no message is generated. *''Not Allow:'' The transaction cannot be released unless the issue is resolved by issuing more material or decreasing the quantity reported.
