This box is unavailable when the value in the '''Function''' box is ''Disassemble''. |- | '''Over Issue Material''' | This checks if the material being issued on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form exceeds the quantity remaining to be issued.[anchor|#_1a86859e-0765-46a4-b4ce-fdd75c5d2835] *''Allow:'' No error message is displayed. *''Warn:'' A warning message is displayed but the transaction can continue. *''Not Allow:'' The transaction cannot be released unless the issue is resolved by returning material or decreasing the quantity reported. Additionally the '''Include Unreleased Batch Qty''' check box will include the quantity on unreleased Materials batches; unreleased batches have a status of ''Balanced'' or ''On Hold''. Checking this option may increase the processing time if there are a large number of unreleased material batches. |- | '''Issue Material Not On Order''' | This option can warn or prevent the entry of a materials transaction for a component not specified on the production order. The options are:[anchor|#_34478111-4346-45c4-9820-19c7e14518fe] *''Allow:'' No error message is displayed. *''Warn:'' A warning message is displayed but the transaction can continue. *''Not Allow:'' The transaction cannot be released unless the issue is resolved by correcting or removing the inventory item or by adding the inventory item to the order by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form.
|- | '''Move on Completed Operations''' | This checks if the operation has a status of ''Completed'' for a move or labor transaction. The options for this setting are:[anchor|#_7eb29a05-bc99-4591-bca4-22e892bad1d0] *''Allow:'' No error message is displayed. *''Warn:'' A warning message is displayed only when the batch is saved but the transaction can continue. If the user releases the batch, no message is generated. *''Not Allow:'' The transaction cannot be released.
|- | '''Over Complete Orders''' | This checks if the production order has a status of ''Completed'' for a move or labor transaction. This is particularly important for the final operation of a production order; the final operation generates a receipt into inventory. This in intended to prevent duplicate and over receipts into inventory. The options for this setting are:[anchor|#_4941357e-3c27-4c75-a803-4b89c0aa3b9b] *''Allow:'' No error message is displayed. *''Warn:'' A warning message is displayed only when the batch is saved but the transaction can continue. If the user releases the batch, no message is generated. *''Not Allow:'' The transaction cannot be released.
|- | '''Default operation move qty''' | If selected, the ''Qty Remaining'' for the operation defaults to the quantity for a move transaction. This does not apply to labor transactions. |}

A rework or repair order can be used to issue an existing item from inventory, do something to it, and return it to stock with the same or different inventory id. There are a number of reasons why this may be necessary:[anchor|#_3cbfca90-bd15-4b94-967d-d43532a13e26] *The item is an old revision and needs to be upgraded. *A component from a supplier was found to be defective and needs to be replaced. *It was returned by a customer or someone else and needs to be inspected and repaired if necessary. *It can be converted into a different item that someone wants. *You want to disassemble it for it&rsquo;s parts and dispose it.
==Create a Repair/Rework Bill of Material== If you frequently do repair work for your customers you might create a repair bill of material for the stock item. You would list the operations to be performed and if required, any materials always used in the process. By having a special bill of material you can also add notes, attach procedures, or add attributes to the bill that will be copied to the production order based on the production order type settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form. ==Create a Production Order Type== On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form, you create an order type for repair and rework orders to help identify them and to use different settings, such as:[anchor|#_72550456-28db-453c-9f2e-280d42ae524e] *Numbering Sequence *WIP and WIP Variance Accounts (only if Posting Class is not used) *Default Costing Method *Copy Notes Settings *Data Entry Settings
==Create the Production Order== To start you need to create a production order for the item you plan to receive into inventory. If the item has a bill of material you can decide if you want to use an existing bill, either the default or a special repair bill, to start and then amend it as necessary by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form. You delete unneeded operations with their materials; change, delete, or add materials; modify overhead and/or tools as required. Be sure to review the backflush check boxes for an operation or material and clear them when necessary.{br}
Alternatively, you can remove the ''BOM ID'' on the '''References''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form. If you do this, you will need to create at least one operation in order to report the quantity completed and issue materials. The first material to add is the inventory item to issue to the production order which can be the same as the item being reworked.{br}
If known if advance, you can add other materials to the details or simply issue them as needed during the rework process; there is no restriction on materials being issued that are not in the production details. If some materials are recoverable and are known in advance, make the quantity required a negative and a receipt will be created to return the item to inventory when you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_10|Materials Wizard] (opened from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form) to create a materials batch.((({S:Warn}Whether or not you use an existing bill of material or manually enter the production details you will need to add the item being issued from inventory for repair and this can be the same item you will return to stock or dispose. Although you cannot specify an inventory item as a component of itself in a bill of material because it would cause a circular reference in MRP Regeneration or the Cost Roll process, you can do this for a production order. ))) If you are using posting classes defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form to specify default WIP and WIP Variance accounts, you can override these settings on the '''References''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] form. ==Returning Materials to Stock== If there are components that are removed and can be used elsewhere or need to be returned to vendor, you can enter a negative quantity on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form. The cost of an item returned to stock is dependent on the ''Default Returns Cost'' settings for warehouses. If the materials need further processing (inspection, disposal, repair, return to vendor, etc.), you should indicate a warehouse bin location that is not included in the quantity available calculations and excluded from MRP.{br}
The cost of materials returned to stock will credit the work in process account specified on the production order and debit the inventory account associated with each inventory item. ==Returning Materials to Vendors== After returning the item to stock, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form to create a vendor return. For more information about vendor returns, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\OrderMgmt_Purchase_Return_Original_Cost_GeneralInfo|Purchase Returns at the Original Cost: General Information] and [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\OrderMgmt_Purchase_Return_Calc_Cost_GeneralInfo|Purchase Returns at the Calculated Cost: General Information]. ==Posting the Completion or Disposal== If the repairs were successful, then you can receive the unit to stock by creating a move or labor transaction. If the unit is lot- or serial-tracked you can use the same lot or serial number or the new one, that is, you can add a suffix to indicate it has been repaired.{br}
If the repairs were not completely successful, then you can enter the scrap quantity on the Move or Labor transaction to complete the production order. Using this method can leave a balance for the WIP amount on the production order. Alternatively, you could receive the item into a disposal location and use an Inventory Issue with an appropriate reason code to charge the costs to whatever account you desire. ==Closing the Production Order== The final step is to close production orders by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_60_00|Close Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM506000|AM506000]) form to zero out any WIP balance and to post those costs to the WIP Variance account. You can update the production order to change the WIP Variance account before closing the order.

All production management transactions use the same logic to determine the order in which to display, select, and/or validate the warehouse bin locations. These transactions are managed on the following forms: [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_10|Materials Wizard], [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]), and [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_10_00|Critical Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM401000|AM401000]). ==Receipts== In order to select a warehouse location for a receipt created as a result of a labor or move transaction the location must have the following boxes selected on the '''Location Table''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form:[anchor|#_89fe45be-2234-4f0e-abb9-7ebba66992e9] *'''Active''' * '''Receipts Allowed''' * '''Assembly Allowed'''
The ''Transaction Warehouse'' defaults to the warehouse specified on a production order.{br}
The default receipt location is determined in the following order and must adhere to the above validation rules:[anchor|#_7bba0398-5ceb-46ee-a06f-b274e96fbcd7] *The location specified on the production order, which was defaulted when the order was created by the following rules. *The location specified in the '''Default Receipt To''' box of the '''General Settings''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. *The location specified in the '''Default Receipt To''' box of the '''General Settings''' tab on [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form when the transaction warehouse is the default warehouse for the stock item. *The location specified in the '''Receiving Location''' box of the '''Location Table''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form when the transaction warehouse is the default warehouse for the stock item.
In the absence of default locations, the qualifying locations are listed in the selection list ordered by pick priority. You can override the warehouse and location as required on the transaction as long as the location is qualified. For example, use a defective material location when the stock item may not be up to specifications and needs to be inspected. ==Issues== If the warehouse is specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] ([~/?ScreenId=AM209000|AM209000]) form without a specific location then it is the transaction warehouse; if not specified, the warehouse specified in the production order is the transaction warehouse. When selecting a warehouse location to issue materials to a production order the location must have the following check boxes selected on the '''Location Table''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form:[anchor|#_5a9a69c9-0287-4adb-91b0-da4736ce44da] *'''Active''' * '''Sales Allowed''' * '''Assembly Allowed'''
The default issue location will be determined in the following order and must adhere to the above validation rules:[anchor|#_c9f3ba00-ac98-445b-bd76-282ef2b70340] *The location specified in the '''Default Issue From''' box of the '''General Settings''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. *The location specified in the '''Default Issue From''' box of the '''General Settings''' tab on [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form when the transaction warehouse is the default warehouse for the stock item. *The location specified in the '''Shipping Location''' box of the '''Location Table''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form when the transaction warehouse is the default warehouse for the stock item.
In the absence of default locations or when an additional location is required, the qualifying locations are selected in order of pick priority.{br}
Where creating a materials batch by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_10|Materials Wizard] form or as a result of backflushing the above rules are applied automatically.{br}
If you are returning materials to stock (negative issue) the issue rules are applied. If the stock item is a by-product then the receipt rules are used.((({S:Warn}The rules are not applied when a location is specified for the material on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_90_00|Production Order Details] form; this will be the only location used. )))

Labor is a component of product cost, both when rolling up the planned costs for bills of material and production orders and when recording the actual times or backflushing the standard times. Recording the actual time spent on production operations and comparing them to the planned costs is part of manufacturing performance reporting. Every production order tracks the variances between planned and actual costs and reports are provided in the module. Even if all or some labor is backflushed you could possibly create a custom inquiry or report to compare the actual labor costs to the ''earned'' or standard costs.{br}
There are two methods to report labor hours and their resultant cost against production orders:[anchor|#_7c5b0534-fdc6-4e48-bc5e-2407e087d55c] #Direct entry by employees using their cost rates or work center standard rates. #Backflushing labor by reporting quantities completed at an operation.
Both methods can be used concurrently. For example, employees will only report labor against milestone operations and the prior secondary operations will be backflushed for labor. Additionally, non-direct labor, labor not attributed to a production order, can be reported to capture their cost in the GL.{br}
Integration with employee time activities (for details, see [HelpRoot_Organization\EP__con_Time_Tracking|Time Activities]) is supported by using the [https://help-2020r1.acumatica.com/(W(52))/Wiki/ShowWiki|Create Labor Time Activities] (AM503000) form if the ''Time Reporting on Activity'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. ==Prerequisites== Whether or not you decide in include the labor element in your costs, the following items are required:[anchor|#_c8c42da3-f6f1-4b24-a103-677f8db44893] *''GL Accounts:'' These are the offset accounts used when labor costs are posted to the Work in Progress account of the production order or indirect labor is reported. *Labor codes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_65_00|Labor Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=AM206500|AM206500]) form: The labor code determines the GL account for labor cost. Direct labor requires a labor account and indirect requires both a labor account and an overhead account. *Work calendar on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_90_00|Work Calendar] ([~/?ScreenId=CS209000|CS209000]) form: All work centers need to have a calendar. *Shifts on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_50_00|Shifts] ([~/?ScreenId=AM205000|AM205000]) form: These are required when adding a work center. Shifts can also be used to factor labor rates for premium hours such as overtime or holidays. *Work centers on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_70_00|Work Centers] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207000|AM207000]) form: **''Standard Cost:'' This is the cost per hour used when calculating planned costs, backflushing labor, and optionally used when employees report labor. **Shifts: You must specify a shift and its associated work calendar and labor code. When employees report their time, they must enter the shift and that defaults the labor code. **''Backflush Labor:'' This will be the default when you add an operation for the work center in bills of material. **Overhead: They are not required but it may be easier to add them to the work center rather than specifying them on the bill of material for each operation. You can use labor overhead rates calculated on the basis of hours and/or labor costs.
==Employees==[anchor|#_8372121a-f1f4-43ef-8e84-581cd18bed24] *Employees, which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_30_00|Employees] ([~/?ScreenId=EP203000|EP203000]) form: **''Production Employee:'' If employees will report direct or indirect labor they must be flagged as a production employee **''Employee Cost:'' If you wish you use the employee cost rate, you must specify the rate on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PM_20_99_00|Labor Cost Rates] ([~/?ScreenId=PM209900|PM209900]) form.
==Production Preferences==[anchor|#_b4145a2f-434f-49bf-bae9-2124250bfb7a] *'''Use Labor Rate''': either ''Standard'' (uses Work Center Standard Cost) or ''Employee'' (use Employee Cost Rate not payroll rate). The work center standard rate is always used when labor is backflushed. *'''Default User Employee ID''': If the logged on user is a production employee, then their employee number is populated on the Labor transaction form.
==Operations in Bills of Material== The setup and run time elements for each operation are used to calculate the planned labor cost of a bill of material and production order. Both are extended by the work center standard rate per hour. Setup time cannot be reported; it is only posted when the operation is backflushed. ==Reporting Actual Hours== The [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) form is used to report hours against production operations as well as the quantity completed, and optionally scrap, at an operation of a production order. This same form is used to report indirect labor.{br}
Additionally, production employees can clock on and off of production orders by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_50_00|Clock Entry] ([~/?ScreenId=AM315000|AM315000]) form or the Acumatica mobile app.[anchor|#_151829e4-7556-41ac-8574-13c0e9ddbc6f] *Reporting of scrap is not allowed *Clock entries must be approved by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_51_60_00|Approve Clock Entries] ([~/?ScreenId=AM516000|AM516000]) form to create a labor transaction batch.
==Accounting for Labor Costs== The WIP account for the production order is debited and the labor account for the labor code is credited. When a quantity completed is reported on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) form, any labor overheads are calculated and debit WIP and credit their respective overhead accounts. You should consider the impact of posting to these accounts, as well as the other cost elements recorded by production management transaction, on your GL. Most companies record their actual factory expenses, such as wages and benefits, equipment costs, production supplies, and utilities to the GL.{br}
If both the actuals and the production order transactions are reported you may be posting the same costs twice. You should consider setting up the manufacturing accounts as accrual accounts and debit these accounts to zero when you post your actual costs.

Production transactions may be entered using hand held devices supporting the Acumatica mobile app similar to transactions for sale orders, purchasing, and inventory. The ''Data Entry'' rules specified for the production order types on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) form are enforced.{br}{TOC}
==Transactions Supported==
The following transactions are available:[anchor|#_529c6559-03b9-4782-9577-8423b3f912a6]
*Scan materials on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_30|Scan Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300030|AM300030]) form
*Scan moves on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_10|Scan Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302010|AM302010]) form
*Scan labor on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_20|Scan Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302020|AM302020]) form

==Setup and Configuration==
The ''Manufacturing Data Collection'' feature is optional and must be enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.{br}

You configure the default options for this feature on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form.{br}

The User Settings on each transaction manage settings specific for the current working mode.{br}

In addition, production employees can clock on and off production orders using the mobile version of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_50_00|Clock Entry] ([~/?ScreenId=AM315000|AM315000]) form without having the ''Manufacturing Data Collection'' feature enabled.

The following is a typical process flow of a production order from time of entry to closing it out in the system. All of these processes are recorded on the '''Events''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form.[anchor|#_4ba7839f-0406-48a8-a58f-a73db8bdc50d][anchor|#_15a48d9c-8a06-4f3e-97dc-f205356a787a][image:UserGuide/Images/MFG_Production_Order_Process_Flow1.png|popup|450px] ==Creating Production Orders== Production orders can be created in any of the following ways:[anchor|#_dbfbaad0-81fb-473d-a050-64678122815a] *Manually by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form *By clicking '''Actions''' > '''Production Orders''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form *By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_51_00_00|Create Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM510000|AM510000]) form *By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_10_00|Critical Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM401000|AM401000]) form to create child production orders linked to a parent production order *By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_40_00_00|MRP Display] ([~/?ScreenId=AM400000|AM400000]) from to create multiple orders
For orders created from MRP or critical materials, the primary bill of material from the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) is used to create the production details. For manually created or from sales orders, the source of the production details can be a bill of material, an estimate managed on the [https://help-2020r1.acumatica.com/(W(92))/Wiki/ShowWiki|Estimate] (AM303000) form, or a configuration managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_75_00|Configuration Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM207500|AM207500]) form.{br}
When created, the orders have a status of ''Planned''. Orders with status do not allocate inventory and cannot be posted with any transactions. ==Releasing Production Orders== Production orders may have their status changed to ''Released'' directly from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form. You can also release multiple orders by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_00_00|Release Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM500000|AM500000]) form. When released, production orders are listed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form and the quantity to product is shown in the '''On Production Supply''' box and the materials allocations in the '''In Production Demand''' box. ==Printing Production Tickets== Production tickets, which you can view in the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\AM_62_50_00|Production Ticket] ([~/?ScreenId=AM625000|AM625000]) report, can be printed directly on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form or multiple tickets printed by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_51_10_00|Print Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM511000|AM511000]) form. If either method is used, the method records the event of printing on the''' Event History''' tab of the order. ==Issue Materials== Material transactions managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form, are used to issue materials to production orders. They can be created in any of the following ways:[anchor|#_f38d2462-4d85-4164-ad41-0267316eef85] *Manually *By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_10|Materials Wizard] form *By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_55_00|Unreleased Material Allocations] ([~/?ScreenId=AM305500|AM305500]) form *When confirming vendor shipments on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_00_00|Vendor Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=AM310000|AM310000]) form *Created and released automatically as a result of backflushing when reporting operation completes by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]) forms.
When released, an inventory issue is created by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]) form to update the component on hand balances as well as the production order details, totals, and work in process balance. You should select the '''Automatically Post on Release''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form to ensure the timely updating of on hand and WIP balances. Alternatively, you can setup an automation schedule for releasing inventory documents by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_10_00|Release IN Documents] ([~/?ScreenId=IN501000|IN501000]) form throughout the day.{br}
Issuing materials changes the status of a production order to ''In Process'' if not already set. ==Posting to Operations== Posting to the production order operations must be done in order to move the order through the production processes. Each company can decide which operations should be reported and which operations can be backflushed when setting up the bills of material. When reporting quantities completed, any prior operations that have not been reported are reported in the same quantity.{br}
Posting to operations changes the status of a production order to ''In Process'' if not already set.{br}
When the last operation is reported, an inventory receipt is created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]) form to update the on hand balance of the item being produced. There are two methods used to post operations:[anchor|#_e5f0748e-8cec-402f-b16d-7567ddad0617] *When you want to post the actual labor hours to a production order, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) form. You can also optionally post the quantities completed and scrapped at the same time. *When you want to report only the quantities completed and scrapped, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]) form. Labor hours and costs are backflushed if set on the operation.
Regardless of which form is used, both a cost transaction on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_90_00|Cost Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM309000|AM309000]) form is created to record the transaction details and a GL batch on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_30_10_00|Journal Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=GL301000|GL301000]) form is created to debit the work in process account and credit the appropriate accrual accounts for labor, tools, machines, and overhead costs. The latter three cost elements are only posted when quantities are reported and the operation is marked for backflush. They are always issued automatically in proportion to the quantity reported. All costs incurred to date are summarized on the production order and production operations '''Totals''' tab. ==Completing Production Orders== When reporting the last operation, if the total of quantity completed is equal to or greater than the quantity planned to produce, the production order status is changed to ''Complete''.{br}
You can manually change the status to ''Complete'' by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form.{br}
When a production order is compete only WIP adjustment transactions managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_80_00|WIP Adjustment] ([~/?ScreenId=AM308000|AM308000]) form can be posted to the production order. ==Closing Production Orders== The final process is to close a production order by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_50_60_00|Close Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM506000|AM506000]) form, which creates the final adjustment to set the work in process balance to zero by creating a cost transaction on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_90_00|Cost Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM309000|AM309000]) form and a GL batch on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_30_10_00|Journal Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=GL301000|GL301000]) form. The offset is added to the WIP Variance account.

This dialog box opens from the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form when you click '''Actions''' > '''Production Order''' on the form toolbar.{br}
You use this dialog box to create and view production orders for any number of sales order lines where the replenishment source of the stock item is ''Manufactured''. If an item does not appear in the list and you think it should, check the following:[anchor|#_2a9b7eae-7c2a-4316-a2f8-fdd88ce6e380] *For the sales order type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_20_10_00|Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=SO201000|SO201000]) form, the '''Allow Production Orders - Approved''' or '''Allow Production Orders - Hold''' check boxes are selected. *The status of the sales order must be other than ''Pending Approval''. *The '''Mark for Production''' check box must be selected in the sales order line. *:((({S:Hint}You can select the '''Make to Order Item''' check box on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form to make the system select the '''Mark for Production''' check box on the sales order line by default. ))) *The '''MTO Order''' check box is selected for the sales order type to make the '''Mark for Production''' check box available in the sales order line. ((({S:Warn} Changes to the sales order line quantity or date do not automatically update the production order. Similarly, deleting the sales order line or deleting or cancelling the sales order do not delete existing production orders. You can however, drill down to the existing production order and make changes to it provided it is in a status that allows changes.{br}
If you try to delete or cancel a production order linked to a sales order, you will be prompted to confirm the deletion or cancellation. ))) ==Alternative Method== The creation of production orders can be deferred to a later time or assigned to another user by selecting the '''Mark for Production''' check box in the line and by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_51_00_00|Create Production Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=AM510000|AM510000]) form. The '''Mark for Production''' check box is automatically selected when you add to a sales order an item with the '''Make to Order Item''' check box on the '''Manufacturing''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. This process does not support creating production orders when the numbering sequence specified in the '''Order Numbering Sequence''' box of the '''General Settings''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_11_00|Production Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201100|AM201100]) has the '''Manual Numbering''' check box selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_10_10|Numbering Sequences] ([~/?ScreenId=CS201010|CS201010]) form. ==Production Orders Dialog Box== The dialog box lists all of the manufactured stock items on the sales order.[anchor|#_2089a3dc-3f17-495d-b10d-e8316aab3b0d] ===Table=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !Element !Description |- | '''Selected''' | Select this to enable the creation of a new production order. Only allowed if one has not been created already. Checking the box on the column header will select all lines. |- | '''Inventory ID''' | This is the inventory ID for the stock item to be manufactured. |- | '''Subitem''' | This column only appears if subitems are enabled. |- | '''Quantity''' | The quantity to manufacture for this stock item; you can enter a different quantity, |- | '''UOM''' | The base unit of measure for the stock item. |- | '''Mark for Production''' | This indicates that a production order should be created or has already been created for the line. This updates the availability calculations according to settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_15_00|Availability Calculation Rules] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201500|IN201500]) form. |- | '''Prod Order Type''' | Enter or select the production order type to create. Only ''Regular'' order types are allowed. The default order type is specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_10_20_00|Production Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AM102000|AM102000]) form. |- | '''Production Nbr''' | This is the production order number if it has been created. You can click the link to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_20_15_00|Production Order Maintenance] ([~/?ScreenId=AM201500|AM201500]) form and make changes once the order is created. |- | '''Status''' | This is the current status of the created production order. The initial status is ''Planned''. |- | '''Qty Completed''' | This is the quantity completed to date for an existing production order. |- | '''Production UOM''' | This is the unit of measure for the production order Qty Completed. |- | '''Line Nbr''' | This is the line number of the sales order and can be used for sorting. |- | colspan="2" | The dialog box contains the following buttons. |- | '''Create''' | Creates production orders for the selected items where a production order has not been already created. |- | '''Cancel''' | Closes the dialog box without saving changes. |}

This topic describes how transactions are used to collect and post costs to production orders and how these transactions affect the general ledger.{br}{TOC} ==Transaction Types and Processing== The following transactions are used to post to production orders:[anchor|#_31e45120-5d55-4be5-84ea-c2d6349d6e63] *Labor (which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_10_00|Labor] ([~/?ScreenId=AM301000|AM301000]) form) **Posts direct labor to production order operations and creates a ''Cost Transaction'' batch. **Allows posting of indirect labor to the indirect labor expense account and creates a ''Cost Transaction'' batch. **If a quantity completed and/or scrap is entered, other costs related to the operation such as overhead, tooling, and/or machines are automatically posted as well in the ''Cost Transaction'' batch. **If there are materials specified for the operation that are marked as backflush and a quantity completed and/or scrap is entered, then a ''Materials'' batch is created and processed. **If the quantity completed is for the last operation, an ''Inventory Receipts'' batch is created. If the quantity completed is negative then an ''Inventory Issues'' batch is created. *Move (which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_20_00|Move] ([~/?ScreenId=AM302000|AM302000]) form) **Same as labor but without posting of labor. *Material (which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_00_00|Materials] ([~/?ScreenId=AM300000|AM300000]) form) **Post materials issues. **Create ''Inventory Issues'' batch for components consumed and an ''Inventory Receipts'' batch for by-products. **If materials are being returned, that is, a negative quantity was entered on the Materials batch or a negative quantity completed was entered on the Labor or Move transaction and there are materials marked as backflush, the ''Inventory Issues'' batch lines have a transaction type of ''Return''. *Vendor shipment (which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_31_00_00|Vendor Shipments] ([~/?ScreenId=AM310000|AM310000]) form) **Creates a materials batch. **Create ''Inventory Issues'' batch for components consumed. **Post the cost to the subcontract totals. *WIP adjustment (which are managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_80_00|WIP Adjustment] ([~/?ScreenId=AM308000|AM308000]) form) **Adjusts the WIP balance and creates a ''Cost Transaction'' batch. **If a production order is cancelled or closed a ''WIP Adjustment'' batch and ''Cost Transaction'' batch are created also.
The cost adjustment batches (managed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AM_30_90_00|Cost Transactions] ([~/?ScreenId=AM309000|AM309000]) form) create a GL batch to update the work in process and the appropriate expense accounts. ==Processing Steps== In order to ensure that all transactions are flow through the system as required, the following actions occur from the Release action of the source batch:[anchor|#_13633bc8-1cd9-402e-828e-a616bcf25215] #All of the related transaction batches are created (''Materials'', ''Cost'', ''Inventory'', and ''GL'') with a status of ''Hold''. A user cannot edit or release the on hold ''Inventory'' or ''GL'' batches because the source is not IN or GL. #All of the related transaction batches are released. #The production orders are updated and the source batch is marked as ''Released''. ((({S:Warn}Should you find a production batch with a status of ''Balanced'' where the batch has a reference to an Inventory or GL batch, do not attempt to release the inventory or GL batch. Release the production source transaction batch again and it will process and release the related transaction batches if they already exist and create any that are missing. You may need to add the '''IN Ref Nbr''' or '''GL Ref Nbr''' to the columns in the details area in order to see the reference. ))) ==Reversing a Transaction== All enterable production transactions can be reversed by entering a negative quantity or hours. The easiest way to accomplish this with a minimum of typing is to find the original transaction batch and create a new batch by copying its settings. You change the appropriate transaction line quantities or hours to a negative value. Then you delete any other lines that you do not need to correct. If batch control totals are used, they must be negative also. Then you release the new batch. When the transaction is to reverse/decrease an inventory receipt from a production order, see [HelpRoot_Manufacturing\AM_PM_NegativeMove|Reversing Production Receipts].((({S:Warn}Cost Transactions cannot be directly entered as they are created by other production transactions. ))) ==Transaction Accounting== Each production order contains the following boxes that get posted as well as the individual cost elements:[anchor|#_dc70c82e-c954-4f84-aaa5-d0e3e74985ec] *'''WIP Total''': This is the sum of all actual costs and is updated for every transaction. *'''MFG to Inventory''': This is the total of the inventory receipts from the production order and is updated by a Labor or Move transaction for the final operation when a quantity complete is entered. *'''WIP Balance''': This is the difference between '''WIP Total''' less '''MFG to Inventory''' [anchor|#_52441f05-36fd-4e7d-8d4a-5088bc368a58] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="40%" ! Process !width="60%" ! Resulting Transactions |- | Enter a production order | No accounting transactions |- | Release a production order | No accounting transactions. Inventory is allocated and is visible on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. |- | Issue materials to a production order | ''WIP Total'' and actual ''Material'' costs are debited.{br}
The stock item Inventory account, or Expense Accrual for non-stock items, is credited using the cost from inventory. Inventory is directly issued by a ''Materials'' batch or indirectly as a result of backflushing by a ''Labor'' or ''Move'' batch. |- | Confirm a vendor shipment | A ''Materials'' batch is created. The subcontract actual totals are updated. |- | Issue labor to production order | Labor transaction only post labor hours and their costs. If a quantity complete and/or scrap quantity is reported, then they will act as a move transaction to recognize other costs.{br}
''WIP Total'' and actual ''Labor'' costs are debited.{br}
Direct Labor is credited using either standard cost from a work center or an employee labor rate. |- | Move Transactions | [anchor|#_b8d762c6-cc46-4c8d-a25a-c57a0f1645fd] *Overhead: ''WIP Total'' is debited. Overhead is credited based on the cost rates from the overheads. *Machine: ''WIP Total'' is debited. Machine is credited for the standard cost rates from the machines. *Tool: ''WIP Total'' is debited. Tool is credited for the unit cost for the Tools. *On the last operation finished items are received into Inventory: The Inventory account is debited. WIP Total is credited.
